{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:31:48.410015", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "so if those workflows triggered from cmd line, can it be controlled then?", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:32:09.033730", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Yes \u2014 CLI triggering doesn't bypass any gate. All controls apply equally whether the dispatch comes from the web UI, `gh`, or the REST API.\n\n- **Who can trigger.** `gh workflow run` requires the caller's token to have `workflow` scope **and** repo write access. For the issue path, anyone who can open or label an issue can trigger it (that's usually wider \u2014 any authenticated user on public repos). So the issue path is the looser door; lock it down with `if:` conditions in `issue-trigger.yml` (e.g. only act on issues from org members) if that matters to you.\n- **Environment reviewer gate.** If `RUNNERS_PAT` lives in an environment with you as required reviewer, the run pauses at the job referencing that environment, regardless of trigger source. CLI-triggered runs sit in \"Waiting\" state until you `gh run view` and approve via web, or:\n  ```bash\n  gh api -X POST repos/<owner>/<repo>/actions/runs/<run-id>/pending_deployments \\\n    -f 'environment_ids[]=<env-id>' -f state=approved -f comment=ok\n  ```\n- **Secret masking / fork exclusion.** Still applied. CLI doesn't change how secrets are injected.\n- **Branch protection.** `workflow_dispatch` runs the workflow file **from the ref you pass** (`--ref <branch>`, defaults to default branch). If you branch-protect `main`, a malicious collaborator can't land a workflow-stealing change there, so CLI dispatch against `main` stays safe. They *could* dispatch against their own branch \u2014 mitigate by not storing secrets outside environments gated on `main`, or restrict `workflow_dispatch` to protected branches (Settings \u2192 Actions \u2192 General \u2192 \"Allow specified actors to bypass required workflows\" etc., plus environment deployment branch rules).\n\nNet: CLI is just another doorway into the same gated hallway. The gates (environment reviewer, fine-grained PAT scope, fork secret exclusion, branch protection) do the actual controlling \u2014 not the UI you triggered from."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:32:25.020663", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "Can we control them by making runtime checks?", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:32:42.035637", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Yes \u2014 you can enforce policy inside the workflow itself, as a belt-and-braces layer on top of the platform gates. Three runtime check patterns, cheapest first:\n\n**1. `if:` conditions on jobs/steps.** Fail-closed before anything sensitive runs:\n```yaml\njobs:\n  run:\n    if: >-\n      github.event_name == 'workflow_dispatch' &&\n      contains(fromJSON('[\"alice\",\"bob\"]'), github.actor) &&\n      github.ref == 'refs/heads/main'\n    uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/coding-agent.yml@main\n```\nSkips (not fails) when conditions don't hold. Good for \"only these actors, only from main, only from this event type.\"\n\n**2. Gate step that hard-fails.** More auditable \u2014 shows up as a red X instead of a silent skip:\n```yaml\n- name: Gate\n  run: |\n    case \"${{ github.actor }}\" in\n      alice|bob) ;;\n      *) echo \"::error::actor ${{ github.actor }} not allowed\"; exit 1 ;;\n    esac\n    [[ \"${{ inputs.runner_label }}\" =~ ^[a-z0-9-]+$ ]] || { echo \"bad runner_label\"; exit 1; }\n```\nUse this to validate **inputs** too (`issue_number` numeric, `runner_label` matches a known pattern) \u2014 platform gates don't validate input shape.\n\n**3. Environment-based dynamic gate.** Route sensitive jobs through an environment whose reviewers / deployment-branch rules you control per-workflow. Combine with step-level `if:` so the environment is only referenced when the job actually needs secrets \u2014 unreferenced runs skip the reviewer prompt and stay fast.\n\nCaveats:\n- Runtime checks run *in the workflow you're trying to protect*. If a collaborator can