{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:33:14.020310", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "can checks be attached to a user workflows?", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:33:35.784791", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Yes \u2014 three layers, in increasing order of \"the user can't remove this\":\n\n**1. Embed checks in the reusable workflow itself.** Since `agent.yml` / `issue-trigger.yml` are callers of `Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/*.yml@<ref>`, put the gate inside the *callee*. Every caller that references `@v1` inherits the check; they can't bypass it without changing their `uses:` ref to a fork or unpinned version:\n```yaml\n# inside autopilot/.github/workflows/coding-agent.yml\njobs:\n  gate:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n      - run: |\n          case \"${{ inputs.issue_number }}\" in ''|*[!0-9]*) exit 1;; esac\n          [[ \"${{ inputs.runner_label }}\" =~ ^[a-z0-9-]+$ ]] || exit 1\n  run:\n    needs: gate\n    ...\n```\nThis is the cheapest \"policy travels with the library\" pattern. The consumer can still swap to `@main` of a fork, so it's a convention, not enforcement.\n\n**2. Organization Required Workflows / Rulesets.** GitHub lets org admins mandate a workflow run on every push/PR in selected repos, regardless of what the repo's own workflows say. Settings: Org \u2192 Rulesets \u2192 \"Require workflows\". The required workflow lives in a control repo you own; it runs in the consumer repo's context but is defined outside it, so consumers can't disable or edit it. Good for \"no workflow may dispatch autopilot from a non-member actor\" style policy.\n\n**3. Environment deployment branch rules + reviewer lists at the org level.** The environment holding `RUNNERS_PAT` / `UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN` can be configured with:\n   - **Deployment branches**: only `main` (or a regex) can reference this environment, so `workflow_dispatch --ref some-attacker-branch` is rejected by the platform before any step runs.\n   - **Required reviewers**: a user or team; the list is set by the repo admin, not the workflow author.\nThese live outside workflow YAML, so editing the workflow doesn't disable them.\n\n**What won't work:** there's no \"hook\" that fires before any workflow runs in a repo. GitHub doesn't let you inject a pre-step into every workflow. If you want universal enforcement, it has to go through one of the three above \u2014 library-side checks (convention), required workflows (org policy), or environment rules (platform gate).\n\nRecommendation for autopilot: put input-shape checks and `author_association` checks inside `coding-agent.yml` / `issue-trigger.yml` in the autopilot repo (layer 1), and park the PATs in environments with `main`-only deployment-branch rules (layer 3). Layer 2 is only worth it if you operate an org and want to force adoption across many consumer repos."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:33:58.158216", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "no, I mean autopilot-selftest", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:34:16.180876", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Yes \u2014 add them directly to the caller files in this repo. Two natural spots:\n\n**In `agent.yml` (workflow_dispatch path)** \u2014 gate before the `uses:` job runs. You can't put an `if:` on `jobs.<id>.uses` that references step outputs, but you *can* put conditions on the job itself, or add a prior `gate` job:\n\n```yaml\njobs:\n  gate:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n      - name: Validate dispatch\n        run: |\n          case \"${{ github.actor }}\" in\n            yaroslav|<other-allowed>) ;;\n            *) echo \"::error::actor ${{ github.actor }} not allowed\"; exit 1 ;;\n          esac\n          case \"${{ inputs.issue_number }}\" in ''|*[!0-9]*) echo \"bad issue_number\"; exit 1 ;; esac\n          [[ \"${{ inputs.runner_label }}\" =~ ^[a-zA-Z0-9-]+$ ]] || { echo \"bad runner_label\"; exit 1; }\n  run:\n    needs: gate\n    uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/coding-agent.yml@main\n    with:\n      runner_label: ${{ inputs.runner_label }}\n      issue_number: ${{ inputs.issue_number }}\n    secrets:\n      UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN }}\n```\n\n**In `issue-trigger.yml` (issues path)** \u2014 use `github.event` fields directly on the `delegate` job:\n\n```yaml\njobs:\n  delegate:\n    if: >-\n      github.event.issue.author_association == 'OWNER' ||\n      github.event.issue.author_association == 'MEMBER' ||\n      github.event.issue.author_association == 'COLLABORATOR'\n    uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/issue-trigger.yml@main\n    ...\n```\nThis skips the delegate for outsiders \u2014 they can still open issues, but autopilot won't pick them up.\n\nCaveats specific to doing this in autopilot-selftest:\n- Checks live in your YAML, so anyone with write access to this repo can edit them out. Protect `.github/workflows/**` with branch protection / required PR review to lock that down.\n- `if:` on the top-level job **skips** (shows neutral), a gate job with `exit 1` **fails** (shows red). Pick based on whether you want audit noise on disallowed triggers.\n- Input validation (`issue_number` numeric, `runner_label` pattern) only matters on the `workflow_dispatch` path \u2014 the issues path derives those from the event payload and can't be forged.\n\nIf you want the policy to survive workflow edits by collaborators, it has to live *outside* this repo (in autopilot's reusable workflow, or in an environment with deployment-branch rules). In-repo checks are a soft layer, useful but editable."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
