{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:37:08.744081", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Yes \u2014 `gh` gives you per-stage visibility. The pattern is: dispatch \u2192 poll \u2192 inspect job/step states \u2192 assert.\n\n**Minimal watcher** (fails fast, shows per-step status):\n```bash\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\nset -euo pipefail\nREPO=yaroslav/autopilot-selftest\nISSUE=1\nRUNNER=yaroslav\n\n# 1. dispatch and capture the run id\ngh workflow run agent.yml -R $REPO -f runner_label=$RUNNER -f issue_number=$ISSUE\nsleep 5\nRUN_ID=$(gh run list -R $REPO --workflow=agent.yml -L1 --json databaseId -q '.[0].databaseId')\necho \"run: https://github.com/$REPO/actions/runs/$RUN_ID\"\n\n# 2. stream to completion, exit non-zero if run failed\ngh run watch $RUN_ID -R $REPO --exit-status\n```\n\n`gh run watch --exit-status` is the one-liner: it prints each job/step transition as it happens and returns non-zero if the run ends in failure.\n\n**Per-stage assertions** \u2014 inspect after (or during) the run:\n```bash\n# full step-by-step breakdown as JSON\ngh run view $RUN_ID -R $REPO --json jobs \\\n  -q '.jobs[] | {name, conclusion, steps: [.steps[] | {name, conclusion}]}'\n\n# fail if a specific step didn't succeed\ngh run view $RUN_ID -R $REPO --json jobs -q \\\n  '.jobs[].steps[] | select(.name==\"Run agent\") | .conclusion' \\\n  | grep -qx success || { echo \"agent step failed\"; exit 1; }\n\n# grep logs of a specific job\ngh run view $RUN_ID -R $REPO --log --job=$(gh run view $RUN_ID -R $REPO --json jobs -q '.jobs[0].databaseId')\n```\n\n**Polling loop** if you need custom per-stage logic (e.g. check an external system between stages):\n```bash\nwhile :; do\n  status=$(gh run view $RUN_ID -R $REPO --json status,conclusion -q '\"\\(.status) \\(.conclusion // \"\")\"')\n  echo \"[$(date +%T)] $status\"\n  case \"$status\" in\n    \"completed success\") exit 0 ;;\n    \"completed \"*)       exit 1 ;;\n  esac\n  # inspect current step mid-flight\n  current=$(gh run view $RUN_ID -R $REPO --json jobs \\\n    -q '.jobs[].steps[] | select(.status==\"in_progress\") | .name' | head -1)\n  echo \"  current step: $current\"\n  sleep 10\ndone\n```\n\n**What you can check at each stage:**\n- Gate job: input validation passed \u2192 `.jobs[] | select(.name==\"gate\") | .conclusion == \"success\"`\n- Runner pickup: runner accepted the job \u2192 step `Set up runner` succeeded\n- Docker image pull \u2192 step `Run agent` reached\n- Agent produced artifacts \u2192 `gh run download $RUN_ID -R $REPO` and inspect\n- PR creation \u2192 `gh pr list --search \"issue-$ISSUE\"`\n- Constraint check \u2192 look at `spec-checks.k.json` posted back, or the comment on the issue\n\nPut all of this in `scripts/selftest.sh` and it becomes the manual equivalent of the nightly smoke job \u2014 run it whenever you want to verify the pipeline end-to-end from your terminal."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:37:50.133598", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "and this script can test both upstream and forked scenarious?", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:38:07.372078", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Yes \u2014 it's the same script, parameterized on which repo you dispatch against and which secret is expected to be live.\n\n```bash\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\nset -euo pipefail\n\nMODE=${1:?usage: selftest.sh <upstream|fork>}\nUPSTREAM=yaroslav/autopilot-selftest\nFORK=yaroslav-fork/autopilot-selftest   # your fork\nISSUE=1\nRUNNER=yaroslav\n\ncase \"$MODE\" in\n  upstream) REPO=$UPSTREAM; EXPECT_PR_IN=$UPSTREAM ;;\n  fork)     REPO=$FORK;     EXPECT_PR_IN=$UPSTREAM ;;  # fork dispatches, PR lands upstream\n  *) echo \"bad mode\"; exit 2 ;;\nesac\n\ngh workflow run agent.yml -R $REPO -f runner_label=$RUNNER -f issue_number=$ISSUE\nsleep 5\nRUN_ID=$(gh run list -R $REPO --workflow=agent.yml -L1 --json databaseId -q '.[0].databaseId')\necho \"run: https://github.com/$REPO/actions/runs/$RUN_ID\"\n\ngh run watch $RUN_ID -R $REPO --exit-status\n\n# Assertion differs by mode: which repo should hold the resulting PR?\npr=$(gh pr list -R $EXPECT_PR_IN --search \"issue-$ISSUE in:title\" --json number,headRepositoryOwner -q '.[0]')\n[ -n \"$pr\" ] || { echo \"no PR in $EXPECT_PR_IN\"; exit 1; }\n\nif [ \"$MODE\" = fork ]; then\n  head_owner=$(echo \"$pr\" | jq -r '.headRepositoryOwner.login')\n  [ \"$head_owner\" = \"${FORK%%/*}\" ] || { echo \"PR head is not the fork\"; exit 1; }\nfi\necho \"ok: $MODE mode, PR #$(echo \"$pr\" | jq -r '.number') in $EXPECT_PR_IN\"\n```\n\nRun both:\n```bash\n./scripts/selftest.sh upstream\n./scripts/selftest.sh fork\n```\n\nWhat actually differs between the two runs:\n- **Dispatch target**: `-R` points at upstream vs. fork. The fork needs `UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN` in *its* secrets; upstream doesn't.\n- **PR landing place**: in upstream mode the PR is opened in the same repo (default `GITHUB_TOKEN`); in fork mode `create-pr` uses `UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN` and opens it cross-repo against upstream base. The assertion checks `headRepositoryOwner` to confirm the cross-repo shape actually happened (otherwise a misconfigured fork would silently fall back to same-repo PRs and the test would falsely pass).\n- **Runner**: same `runner_label` works for both if both repos can reach the same self-hosted runner. If not, pass a different label per mode.\n\nOne gotcha: the two modes can't share an issue number unless the fork is up to date with upstream (fork runs check out the fork's tree). Easiest is to keep issue #1 identical in both repos, or pass `ISSUE` as a second arg."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
