{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:38:42.289702", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "For the driving script itself \u2014 no, if you're already `gh auth login`'d on your machine. Your local gh auth token needs:\n\n- `workflow` scope \u2014 to call `gh workflow run`. Standard `gh auth login` with \"web browser\" grants this by default.\n- Read access to both repos (upstream + fork) to list runs, view steps, and search PRs. If you own both, your login covers it.\n\nThat's it. The script never touches `RUNNERS_PAT` or `UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN` \u2014 those live in repo/environment secrets and are consumed by the workflow at runtime, not by your terminal.\n\nWhen you *would* need a separate PAT:\n- **Running the script from CI** (e.g. the nightly smoke job I mentioned earlier). A workflow's default `GITHUB_TOKEN` has `workflow` scope only for its own repo, and can't dispatch workflows in another repo. If you want the nightly job in upstream to also dispatch fork's `agent.yml`, it needs a PAT with `workflow` scope on the fork \u2014 store as `SELFTEST_DISPATCH_PAT`.\n- **Running from a machine where `gh` isn't authenticated** (e.g. a shared CI box). Set `GH_TOKEN=<pat>` in the environment before running.\n\nQuick check you have enough locally:\n```bash\ngh auth status              # shows scopes\ngh workflow run --help      # no-op, just verifies auth works\n```\n\nIf `gh auth status` lists `workflow` in the scopes for both repos' host, you're done \u2014 no new PAT needed."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
