{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:53:49.714257", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "Select repository that can access this package using GitHub actions. What exactly this means for public package?", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:54:10.028103", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "That setting controls **which repos' workflow `GITHUB_TOKEN` gets automatic access to this package**. For a *public* package, it doesn't affect who can pull it \u2014 it affects who can **write** to it and whether workflows can pull without an explicit `docker login`.\n\nBreakdown for a public ghcr.io image:\n\n- **Unauthenticated `docker pull` from anywhere**: always works. Public = world-readable. This setting doesn't gate that.\n- **Workflow in a linked repo using `GITHUB_TOKEN`**: that repo's Actions can `docker pull` *and* `docker push` to this package without needing a PAT, because `GITHUB_TOKEN` is granted `read:packages` / `write:packages` on the linked package automatically. The `packages: write` job permission is still required in the workflow YAML, but no extra secret setup.\n- **Workflow in an unlinked repo**: its `GITHUB_TOKEN` cannot push to this package at all, regardless of public status. It can still pull via anonymous access, but if your workflow does `docker login ghcr.io -u ... -p $GITHUB_TOKEN`, the login will fail with a not-linked package \u2014 you'd need to skip the login or use a PAT.\n- **Inherit access from repo** option: automatically links the package to whatever repo's `GITHUB_TOKEN` built/pushed it. Recommended default \u2014 removes manual linking steps as you add consumer repos.\n\nWhy it matters even for public packages:\n1. **Push access.** Only linked repos can push new versions via `GITHUB_TOKEN`. If autopilot-ws's image is published from `Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot-ws`, that repo must be in the access list; otherwise the publish job fails.\n2. **Private-to-public promotion later.** If you ever flip the package to private, only linked repos' workflows keep working. Setting the access list correctly now avoids a scramble later.\n3. **Fork safety.** Unlinked forks can't push to the canonical package even if they try \u2014 the access list is the enforcement layer. Public visibility doesn't relax this.\n\nPractical recommendation for autopilot-ws: add `Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot-ws` (the publisher) to the access list with inherit access, and leave autopilot-selftest / consumer repos off \u2014 they only need to pull, which works anonymously for a public package."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:55:10.099596", "event": "Notification", "source": "input", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "hook_event_name": "Notification", "message": "Claude is waiting for your input", "notification_type": "idle_prompt"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:57:39.414221", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "why in selftest I see strange long jobs names like ? delegate / image-digest / fetch-manifest", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:57:54.604394", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Those are **reusable-workflow job paths**. When a job's `uses:` points at another workflow, GitHub renders the resulting job name in the UI (and in `gh run view`) as `outer-job / inner-job / ...`, one segment per level of nesting.\n\nMapping what you're seeing:\n\n- `delegate` \u2014 the top-level job in *this* repo's `issue-trigger.yml` (`jobs.delegate` on line 15). That's the caller.\n- `delegate / image-digest` \u2014 `delegate` uses autopilot's reusable `issue-trigger.yml`, which internally has a job named `image-digest` that `uses:` autopilot's `image-digest.yml`.\n- `delegate / image-digest / fetch-manifest` \u2014 that `image-digest.yml` has a job named `fetch-manifest` (the actual step that resolves the ghcr manifest SHA). Three levels deep because reusable workflows were chained three times.\n\nSo the path reads top-down: **consumer repo job \u2192 library workflow's internal job \u2192 library workflow it called \u2192 that workflow's internal job**. Each `uses:` adds a segment.\n\nWhy it looks strange:\n- You don't *write* those names in your YAML \u2014 they come from the callee workflows, which live in `Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot`.\n- There's no way to rename them from the caller side; the segments are owned by whoever defined each workflow.\n- A flat `run:` step job would just be `delegate`. The nesting only appears when workflows call other workflows.\n\nPractically: if you want cleaner names, shorten the `jobs.<id>` identifiers in the autopilot library (e.g. rename `image-digest` \u2192 `digest`, `fetch-manifest` \u2192 `fetch`). But the hierarchical rendering itself is baked into GitHub Actions \u2014 you can't collapse it."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:58:47.454122", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "these are verbose and ugly, why can it be fetch-manifest, parse-digest, etc ?", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-22T23:59:08.153557", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Because in autopilot they're each defined as a separate **job** (or a separate reusable workflow), not as steps within one job. That's a design choice in the library, not a GitHub constraint.\n\nTwo knobs decide how a piece of logic shows up in the UI:\n\n1. **Step vs. job.** Steps inside a single job don't get their own node in the run graph \u2014 they're collapsed under the job's name. Jobs each render as their own node, with the verbose reusable-workflow path if they're called via `uses:`.\n2. **Inline job vs. reusable workflow.** A job defined inline (with `steps:`) shows as `<job-name>`. A job defined via `uses:` shows as `<caller-job> / <callee-job>`, and recurses for every further `uses:`.\n\nSo `fetch-manifest` and `parse-digest` being their own segments means autopilot split them into **separate jobs in separate reusable workflows**. Reasons that justify it:\n\n- You want the digest available as a **workflow output** that other jobs/workflows can consume. Outputs only cross job boundaries; within a single job, step outputs stay local.\n- Each job needs a different `runs-on` or different permissions.\n- You want independent re-runnability / caching boundaries.\n\nReasons that *don't* justify it (and produce the ugliness you're seeing):\n\n- Just wanting to \"organize\" two shell commands. That's what steps are for.\n- Wanting visual separation in logs. Step names already give you that, without the `/` path nesting.\n\nCleanup path in autopilot, if you own it:\n\n```yaml\n# instead of two reusable workflows chained:\njobs:\n  digest:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    outputs:\n      sha: ${{ steps.parse.outputs.sha }}\n    steps:\n      - id: fetch\n        run: gh api ... > manifest.json\n      - id: parse\n        run: echo \"sha=$(jq -r .config.digest manifest.json)\" >>$GITHUB_OUTPUT\n```\n\nThat collapses three path segments into one job named `digest`, and logs show `fetch` / `parse` as steps under it. Same functionality, flatter graph. The only reason to keep them as separate jobs is if something else actually calls `image-digest.yml` as a reusable workflow independently \u2014 otherwise it's splitting for splitting's sake.\n\nShort version: the verbose names are a symptom of over-decomposition in the library. Fix is upstream in autopilot \u2014 merge sibling jobs into steps unless a job boundary is load-bearing."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
