{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T00:00:50.178566", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Continuing:\n\n- Steps 4 \"Load cached image\" (skipped \u2014 no cache hit) and 11 \"Post Cache Docker image\" (skipped \u2014 because the job already failed) are unrelated to the root cause. The only real failure is step 6 **\"Run constraint checks\"**.\n\nLog retrieval is **403** via anonymous API \u2014 logs require auth, so I can't read the actual failure text from here. To see the error:\n\n```bash\ngh run view 24807776289 -R Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot-selftest \\\n  --log-failed --job 72609142949\n```\n\nor open https://github.com/Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot-selftest/actions/runs/24807776289/job/72609142949\n\nGiven the state of the repo, the most likely cause is one of:\n1. `spec.k.json` points at a feature whose constraints legitimately fail against the current tree (the `selftest_shape` feature's 3 constraints \u2014 we just saw them pass locally, but the CI job may be checking a different scope or path).\n2. The `Run constraint checks` step invokes `check_spec_constraints.py` inside the Docker image, and `$PROJECT_ROOT` inside the container resolves to a path where `spec.k.json` isn't visible (mount issue).\n3. The image pulled via digest doesn't contain `constraints_tool` on the expected path.\n\nOpen the log and it should say within a couple of lines which constraint id failed or whether the tool itself errored. Paste the failing lines back and I can narrow it down."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T00:01:38.162033", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "showme actual workflow file, related to digest for example", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T00:02:06.078148", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Here's `image-digest.yml` from `Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot`. Notes on what maps to what you saw in the run graph:\n\n- Two jobs \u2192 two path segments. `fetch-manifest` (line 20) and `parse-digest` (line 39) each render as their own node: `<caller-job> / image-digest / fetch-manifest` and `.../ parse-digest`.\n- **They're split for a real reason here**: `parse-digest` declares workflow-level `outputs` (`digest`, `image`, lines 11\u201317) that callers consume via `needs.image-digest.outputs.digest`. That output plumbing only works at the job level, so collapsing them into one job would require changing the callee's output declaration \u2014 not just a cosmetic rename.\n- But the split between `fetch-manifest` and `parse-digest` is **not** load-bearing. They could be one job with two steps:\n  ```yaml\n  jobs:\n    digest:\n      runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n      outputs:\n        digest: ${{ steps.p.outputs.digest }}\n        image:  ${{ steps.p.outputs.image }}\n      steps:\n        - id: f\n          run: |\n            manifest=$(docker manifest inspect \"${{ inputs.image_repo }}:latest\")\n            echo \"$manifest\" | python3 -c '...' >> \"$GITHUB_OUTPUT\"\n        - id: p\n          run: |\n            # parse step reads from step f's output\n  ```\n  That would render as a single `image-digest / digest` node in callers \u2014 one segment shorter. The two-job form just pays the cost of spinning up two runners and passing JSON across job outputs for no added capability.\n\nIf you want the same collapse applied to the other verbose chains (`check-constraints`, the issue-trigger delegate), the pattern is the same: merge jobs whose outputs aren't consumed by siblings into a single job with multiple steps. I can draft a PR to autopilot flattening `image-digest.yml` if you want."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
