{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T00:14:57.422782", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "what is reusable workflow entirely ?", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T00:15:12.456747", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "A \"reusable workflow\" is a workflow file that another workflow calls via `uses:`, instead of running on its own events. That's the mechanism autopilot is built on.\n\nThe relevant contrast:\n\n**Normal workflow** \u2014 lives in `.github/workflows/foo.yml`, has its own `on:` trigger (`push`, `pull_request`, `workflow_dispatch`, etc.), runs its jobs directly when that event fires. Self-contained.\n\n**Reusable workflow** \u2014 lives in `.github/workflows/foo.yml` but its `on:` is `workflow_call:`. It declares `inputs:`, `secrets:`, `outputs:`. It doesn't run on any event by itself. It runs only when another workflow invokes it:\n```yaml\njobs:\n  somejob:\n    uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/check-constraints.yml@main\n    with: { ... }\n    secrets: { ... }\n```\nThink of it as a \"workflow function\" \u2014 the caller passes arguments, the callee runs, returns outputs.\n\nWhy autopilot uses them: one copy of the logic in `Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot`, N consumer repos (selftest, rslite, future marketplace users) each with a tiny caller file that forwards inputs. Update the callee \u2192 all consumers get the fix without touching their own code. That's the marketplace model.\n\n**\"Give up the reusable workflow entirely\"** meant: don't call autopilot's workflow via `uses:`. Instead, copy-paste the constraint-check jobs directly into `autopilot-selftest/.github/workflows/check-constraints.yml` \u2014 steps, `docker pull`, `check_spec_constraints.py`, everything. No cross-repo call, no nesting, so the UI shows flat job names like `fetch-manifest` with no path prefix. The cost is that autopilot-selftest now owns a full copy of the logic, and any bug fix in autopilot wouldn't propagate \u2014 you'd have to re-copy it. That's why it's a bad tradeoff for anything beyond a one-off repo.\n\nTL;DR: reusable workflow = callable library workflow. Giving it up = inlining the library into the caller, which buys you flat names at the cost of code duplication."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T00:16:06.780731", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "reusable workflow is marketplace workflow specifically or this means workflows orgaqnization in which repo then?", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T00:16:23.269704", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Different concepts. \"Reusable workflow\" and \"marketplace workflow\" are not the same thing, though they can overlap.\n\n**Reusable workflow** \u2014 a GitHub Actions feature. Any workflow file with `on: workflow_call:` that another workflow invokes via `uses:`. It's a mechanism for composition. Lives anywhere: same repo, another repo in the same org, a public repo on github.com. Nothing to do with the marketplace.\n\n**Marketplace workflow / action** \u2014 a *distribution* concept. \"Marketplace\" is github.com/marketplace, a catalog where repos publish themselves so others can discover them. You publish by tagging a release and filling out marketplace metadata. What you *actually consume* is still just a workflow or action referenced by `uses:`. The marketplace is a storefront, not a runtime mechanism.\n\nSo: a reusable workflow can be consumed whether or not it's listed on the marketplace. Publishing to the marketplace is optional polish; the `uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/check-constraints.yml@main` reference works either way.\n\n**Three scopes where reusable workflows live**, in order of coupling:\n\n1. **Same repo.** `uses: ./.github/workflows/foo.yml` \u2014 organizational tool for splitting a big workflow into composable pieces inside one repo. No cross-repo story. This is what `autopilot/check-constraints.yml` does when it calls `./.github/workflows/image-digest.yml` \u2014 both files are in the autopilot repo.\n\n2. **Another repo in your org (or public repos).** `uses: org/repo/.github/workflows/foo.yml@ref` \u2014 this is what makes a library. Consumer repos pin by ref (`@v1`, `@main`, SHA). Private reusable workflows in an org work too, if the org settings allow it. This is the mode autopilot-selftest uses to consume autopilot.\n\n3. **Published on the Marketplace.** Same `uses:` syntax, but discoverable via github.com/marketplace search and has a listing page. For *workflows* specifically, marketplace listing is limited \u2014 it's more typical for *actions* (the `uses: actions/checkout@v4`-style composite/docker/js actions). Reusable workflows are often distributed just by being in a public repo without a marketplace listing.\n\nSo in autopilot's case: you're using scope 2 (cross-repo reusable workflow in a public repo). Whether you ever click \"Publish to Marketplace\" in the autopilot repo is a separate question \u2014 it only affects discoverability, not how selftest consumes it.\n\nShort version:\n- **Reusable workflow** = the YAML mechanism (`workflow_call` + `uses:`).\n- **Marketplace** = an optional public catalog.\n- Autopilot is a reusable workflow consumed cross-repo; marketplace publishing is orthogonal."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
