{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T00:19:26.044786", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "`delegate` is just the **job id** you picked for the top-level job in your selftest caller workflow. It has no special meaning to GitHub \u2014 it's the name of the one job in `autopilot-selftest/.github/workflows/check-constraints.yml`, which happens to do nothing except forward to the reusable workflow via `uses:`.\n\nStructurally:\n\n```yaml\njobs:\n  delegate:                                              # \u2190 you named it \"delegate\"\n    uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.../check-constraints.yml@main\n```\n\n- `jobs.<id>` \u2014 every workflow must have at least one job, and each job needs an id. `delegate` is the id. You could rename it to anything: `run`, `check`, `go`, `x`.\n- A job whose body is just `uses:` (no `steps:`) is called a **job that calls a reusable workflow**. It's a pure forwarder \u2014 the actual work runs inside the called workflow, on its jobs/runners.\n- The id was named `delegate` because the job's only role is to delegate to the library workflow in autopilot. It's a naming convention, not a keyword.\n- In the run graph UI, this id becomes the **first segment** of the path (`delegate / image-digest / fetch-manifest`). Which is why renaming it (or setting `name:` on it) changes that outermost label.\n\nIf you rename it to `check-constraints` as I did in the last edit, the path becomes `check-constraints / image-digest / fetch-manifest` \u2014 same structure, just a different label on the outer segment."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T00:19:47.473914", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "you named it delegate. Whay we need this name? and such structural nesting?>", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T00:20:07.001808", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Two separate questions \u2014 both have firm technical answers:\n\n**Why any name at all?**\n\nGitHub Actions requires every workflow to have at least one job, and every job needs an id. A reusable workflow can only be invoked from inside a job (`jobs.<id>.uses:`), never at the workflow top level. So you can't write:\n\n```yaml\n# NOT VALID\non: push\nuses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/...@main\n```\n\nYou have to write:\n\n```yaml\non: push\njobs:\n  <something>:              # \u2190 required, must exist, must have an id\n    uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/...@main\n```\n\n`delegate` is just the id I chose for that `<something>`. Any name works. It carries no semantics. I picked `delegate` because the job's sole purpose is to delegate to the library.\n\n**Why the structural nesting?**\n\nBecause a reusable workflow can't be triggered by events on its own \u2014 only called. The selftest repo has to own the trigger (`on: push`, `on: issues`, `on: workflow_dispatch`) because only the consumer repo sees those events. So the architecture forces at least one layer:\n\n- **Consumer side**: owns `on:`. Has a forwarder job. One segment in the path.\n- **Library side**: owns the logic. Reusable (`on: workflow_call`). One or more jobs.\n\nInside the library, a second layer appears when one reusable workflow calls another (autopilot's `check-constraints.yml` calls `image-digest.yml`). That split exists because `image-digest.yml` is also used by `coding-agent.yml` \u2014 it's shared code, factored into its own file. Merging it into each caller would duplicate logic; keeping it separate adds a path segment.\n\nSo the three segments of `delegate / image-digest / fetch-manifest` correspond exactly to three real things:\n\n| Segment | Represents |\n|---|---|\n| `delegate` | \"the selftest repo received a `push` event and forwarded it\" |\n| `image-digest` | \"the check-constraints library shared its digest-resolution logic with coding-agent by extracting it\" |\n| `fetch-manifest` | \"the digest resolver does its first step \u2014 fetch manifest from ghcr\" |\n\nEach segment is a unit of reuse. None of them are decorative. The only way to eliminate a segment is to give up that unit of reuse (inline it). The name of any segment can be anything; the *existence* of each segment is structural.\n\nShort answer:\n- **Name `delegate`**: arbitrary, pick what you like.\n- **Nesting**: baked in \u2014 it's the price of having a library workflow callable by multiple consumers. No GitHub-level feature removes it; only inlining does."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T00:21:21.899525", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "so if we have structure delegate: (fetch-manifest, parse-digfest, check-constraints). Why It named: delegate / image-digest / fetch-manifest ?", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T00:21:41.172702", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Because your mental model is missing a layer. The tree isn't flat \u2014 there's a `jobs.image-digest` **wrapper job** inside autopilot's check-constraints.yml, and *it* is what calls image-digest.yml. Every `uses:` across workflows lives inside a job, and that job's id becomes a path segment.\n\nActual structure:\n\n```\nautopilot-selftest/.github/workflows/check-constraints.yml\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 jobs.delegate                         \u2190 segment 1\n    \u2514\u2500\u2500 uses: autopilot/.../check-constraints.yml\n\n        autopilot/.github/workflows/check-constraints.yml\n        \u251c\u2500\u2500 jobs.image-digest              \u2190 segment 2 (a wrapper job)\n        \u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 uses: ./image-digest.yml\n        \u2502\n        \u2502       autopilot/.github/workflows/image-digest.yml\n        \u2502       \u251c\u2500\u2500 jobs.fetch-manifest    \u2190 segment 3 (leaf)\n        \u2502       \u2514\u2500\u2500 jobs.parse-digest      \u2190 segment 3 (leaf)\n        \u2502\n        \u2514\u2500\u2500 jobs.check-constraints         \u2190 segment 2 (sibling leaf)\n            \u2514\u2500\u2500 steps: [...]\n```\n\nWhich gives you exactly these run-graph paths:\n\n- `delegate / image-digest / fetch-manifest`\n- `delegate / image-digest / parse-digest`\n- `delegate / check-constraints`\n\nWhy `image-digest` appears as a segment even though you never wrote it in the selftest: it's the **id of the wrapper job** in autopilot's check-constraints.yml, the job whose body is `uses: ./image-digest.yml`. That job literally exists \u2014 it has its own runner allocation, its own state in the UI \u2014 and its id is what the path shows. If you rename `jobs.image-digest` \u2192 `jobs.digest` inside autopilot/check-constraints.yml, the path becomes `delegate / digest / fetch-manifest`.\n\nSo the rule: **every `uses:` sits inside a job; that job's id is a path segment; you can't have a `uses:` without a wrapping job.** Three `uses:`-crossings in the chain = three segments. `fetch-manifest`, `parse-digest`, `check-constraints` are siblings at different depths \u2014 two of them under `image-digest`, one next to it \u2014 because of how the autopilot library chose to factor its files.\n\nThe flat view `delegate: (fetch-manifest, parse-digest, check-constraints)` would only be true if autopilot's check-constraints.yml had inlined image-digest.yml as three sibling jobs instead of calling it via `uses:`."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
