{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T13:32:59.868242", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Four realistic alternatives, ranked by how flat the run graph becomes vs. what you give up:\n\n**A. Composite action for digest resolution** (biggest win for graph, smallest code change)\n\nConvert `image-digest.yml` from a reusable workflow into a **composite action** at `autopilot/.github/actions/image-digest/action.yml`. Composite actions are consumed at the *step* level, not the job level, so they don't add path segments.\n\nThen `autopilot/check-constraints.yml` becomes one job:\n```yaml\njobs:\n  check-constraints:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n      - id: digest\n        uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/actions/image-digest@main\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n      - name: Cache Docker image\n        ...\n      - name: Run constraint checks\n        env:\n          AGENT_IMAGE: ${{ steps.digest.outputs.image }}\n        ...\n```\n\nPaths collapse to: `delegate / check-constraints` \u2014 two segments, period. `fetch-manifest` and `parse-digest` become steps under `check-constraints`, visible in logs but not in the run graph.\n\nTradeoffs: composite actions run on the caller's runner (no separate runner for digest resolution) and can't have an independent `runs-on`. For a cheap `docker manifest inspect` call that's fine. Composite actions can't call other composite actions across nesting more than a few levels, but this case is shallow.\n\n**B. Collapse `fetch-manifest` + `parse-digest` into one job in image-digest.yml** (keep it reusable, just flatter)\n\nMerge the two jobs into one with two steps:\n```yaml\njobs:\n  digest:\n    name: digest\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    outputs:\n      digest: ${{ steps.parse.outputs.digest }}\n      image:  ${{ steps.parse.outputs.image }}\n    steps:\n      - id: fetch\n        run: docker manifest inspect ... > manifest.json\n      - id: parse\n        run: ... >> $GITHUB_OUTPUT\n```\n\nPaths:\n- `delegate / image-digest / digest`\n- `delegate / check-constraints`\n\nOne segment shorter for the digest chain. Still three deep. Preserves reusability across `coding-agent.yml` + `check-constraints.yml`. Easiest change.\n\n**C. Inline `image-digest.yml` into each caller workflow** (flatten by sacrificing DRY)\n\nCopy the digest job directly into `autopilot/check-constraints.yml` and `autopilot/coding-agent.yml`. Delete `image-digest.yml`. Paths:\n- `delegate / fetch-manifest`\n- `delegate / parse-digest`\n- `delegate / check-constraints`\n\nAll flat at two segments. Downside: digest logic lives in two places inside autopilot; fixing a bug means editing both. Manageable because both files live in the same repo \u2014 easy to keep in sync \u2014 but still duplication.\n\n**D. Hybrid \u2014 composite action for digest + inline constraint check** (flattest possible without giving up the library boundary)\n\nSame as A, plus: have the autopilot/check-constraints.yml be a reusable workflow with a single job `check-constraints` whose steps include the composite action. Path: `delegate / check-constraints`. One segment past the consumer's own job. That's the structural floor \u2014 you can't get below it without inlining the whole thing into the selftest (which defeats the library).\n\n**Recommendation:** **A**. It's the cleanest because composite actions are specifically designed for \"shared steps\" and don't pollute the run graph with wrapper jobs. `image-digest` is only ever used as a \"resolve a ref then continue\" helper \u2014 never independently \u2014 so it has no reason to be a separate job at all. Change it once in autopilot, every consumer workflow gets flatter paths for free.\n\nIf you don't want to touch autopilot as much, **B** is a 3-line change (merge two jobs into one) that saves one segment per digest call.\n\n**C** is only worth it if you're planning to also eliminate other reusable-workflow nesting for consistency. Not recommended for just this case."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T13:33:56.967647", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "but from perspectove of testing it locally using act and test case, how we will test those actions?", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T13:34:33.001468", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Good question \u2014 the choice affects what `act` can target and how you assert on results. Autopilot already has the pattern: `act-step-runner.yml`. The structure change just shifts what that harness invokes.\n\n**Current structure (reusable workflow `image-digest.yml` with two jobs)**\n\nTestable at three granularities:\n```bash\n# run the whole library file\nact workflow_call -W autopilot/.github/workflows/image-digest.yml \\\n    --input image_repo=ghcr.io/clockwork-pilot/autopilot-ws\n\n# run one job in isolation\nact -j fetch-manifest -W autopilot/.github/workflows/image-digest.yml\n\n# run the wrapping caller that consumes its outputs (end-to-end)\nact push -W autopilot-selftest/.github/workflows/check-constraints.yml\n```\nWorkflow-level `outputs:` mean you can assert on `digest` / `image` from outside \u2014 write the output to a file in a final step and diff it against a golden value. This is exactly what `act-step-runner.yml` was built for: load a case, run a step or job, capture outputs, compare.\n\n**Option A \u2014 composite action (`autopilot/.github/actions/image-digest`)**\n\nComposite actions can't be invoked standalone by `act` \u2014 they must be consumed from a workflow step. So testing means a **tiny harness workflow** that does nothing but call the action and emit its outputs:\n\n```yaml\n# autopilot/.github/workflows/test-image-digest.yml\non: [workflow_dispatch, workflow_call]\njobs:\n  test:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    outputs:\n      digest: ${{ steps.d.outputs.digest }}\n      image:  ${{ steps.d.outputs.image }}\n    steps:\n      - id: d\n        uses: ./.github/actions/image-digest\n        with:\n          image_repo: ${{ inputs.image_repo }}\n      - run: echo \"${{ steps.d.outputs.digest }}\" > /tmp/digest.txt\n      - uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4\n        with: { name: digest, path: /tmp/digest.txt }\n```\n\nThen `act workflow_dispatch -W .../test-image-digest.yml --input image_repo=...` runs it. You lose the ability to invoke `fetch-manifest` / `parse-digest` as independent jobs \u2014 they're steps now, so granularity drops: you can test the *composite as a whole*, but not the fetch and parse halves separately. For a short `docker manifest inspect | python parse` pipeline that's fine; for anything more complex, you lose valuable isolation.\n\n**Option B \u2014 collapse fetch + parse into one job, keep image-digest.yml reusable**\n\nBest middle ground for testability. The job still has workflow-level outputs, so existing `act-step-runner.yml`-style tests keep working with no changes. You lose the ability to run `fetch-manifest` and `parse-digest` as separate jobs, but they were never called independently \u2014 the split was artificial. Steps are still named (`fetch`, `parse`) so `act` logs show each, and step outputs (`steps.fetch.outputs.*`) are still assertable *inside* the job. Just not across jobs.\n\n**Option C \u2014 inline image-digest into each caller**\n\nWorst for local testing. You'd duplicate test cases: one run against check-constraints.yml's copy, one against coding-agent.yml's copy. Any fix needs updating both places and both test suites. Don't do this unless you have a strong reason.\n\n---\n\n**Practical table \u2014 what `act` can invoke under each structure**\n\n| Structure | Run as standalone | Assert via workflow outputs | Test in isolation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Reusable workflow (current) | \u2705 `act -W image-digest.yml` | \u2705 yes | \u2705 per job |\n| Reusable workflow, one job (B) | \u2705 same | \u2705 yes | \ud83d\udfe1 per step only |\n| Composite action (A) | \u274c needs harness workflow | \u2705 via harness | \ud83d\udfe1 as a whole |\n| Inlined (C) | \u274c no library file | \ud83d\udfe1 via caller | \u274c no isolation |\n\n**Recommendation for testability:** **B**. It keeps `image-digest.yml` as a standalone reusable workflow (`act -W image-digest.yml` just works), keeps workflow-level outputs (easy assertions), drops one path segment, and matches the existing `act-step-runner.yml` pattern with no changes. A is theoretically cleaner for runtime graph but pays a tax on local testing \u2014 you need a harness workflow solely to make it callable.\n\nIf you already have test cases keyed on individual jobs (`fetch-manifest` or `parse-digest` being invoked separately), go with B \u2014 they become step invocations on the same job, which `act-step-runner.yml` already handles. If you have no such fine-grained tests and the parse logic is trivial (it is \u2014 5 lines of Python), A is acceptable."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
