{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T13:37:36.529880", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Yes, and it's a good reason to pick a structure that keeps the harness useful. Reading `act-step-runner.yml`: it takes a workflow file + \"step_id\" (really a job id) + JSON inputs, and dispatches via `act`. It doesn't care *what* structure the target has \u2014 it just needs a job it can invoke. That constraint shapes the choice:\n\n**Works directly with current structure and Option B** \u2014 the harness targets a reusable workflow's job:\n```yaml\nuses: ./.github/workflows/act-step-runner.yml\nwith:\n  workflow: image-digest.yml\n  step_id: fetch-manifest            # current\n  # or step_id: digest               # Option B after merging jobs\n  inputs_json: '{\"image_repo\": \"ghcr.io/clockwork-pilot/autopilot-ws\"}'\n```\n\nNo change to the harness, no change to test cases beyond the step_id. The harness runs `act -j <step_id>` under the hood (that's what `.github/scripts/act-step-dispatch.sh` almost certainly does).\n\n**Breaks for Option A (composite action)** \u2014 `act -j` can't target a composite action; only jobs are invocable. You'd need to wrap the composite action in a test-only job to regain a `step_id` to target:\n```yaml\n# autopilot/.github/workflows/image-digest-test.yml\njobs:\n  fetch-manifest:                    # same id as the old job, for test-case stability\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n      - uses: ./.github/actions/image-digest\n        id: d\n        with: { image_repo: ${{ inputs.image_repo }} }\n```\nNow `act-step-runner.yml` keeps working against `workflow: image-digest-test.yml, step_id: fetch-manifest`, but you've added a file whose sole purpose is to be the test entry point. That's overhead for every composite action you extract.\n\n**Breaks for Option C (inlined)** \u2014 the digest jobs no longer exist as a standalone file; they live inside `check-constraints.yml` and `coding-agent.yml`. You'd run `step_id: fetch-manifest` twice, one per host file, duplicating test-case config.\n\n**Implication for your decision:** continuing with `act-step-runner.yml` as the sole test harness is easiest if each testable unit remains a **job in a standalone reusable workflow**. That points at:\n\n- **Current structure** \u2014 works as-is, every test case keeps its step_id.\n- **Option B** \u2014 works after renaming one step_id (`fetch-manifest` \u2192 `digest`), everything else intact.\n- **Option A** \u2014 requires adding a test-only wrapper workflow per composite action; maintenance tax.\n- **Option C** \u2014 test cases fan out across consumers; don't.\n\nSo if keeping the harness is a hard requirement, the honest answer is: **B is the flattest structure compatible with the existing test pattern**. A is structurally prettier for runtime but costs you harness compatibility. I'd pick B."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T13:39:04.457840", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "but what if we add this job wrapper to the same act-step-runner.yml just to keep less files count?", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T13:39:34.706799", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Yes, and it's a reasonable consolidation \u2014 `act-step-runner.yml` is test infrastructure, so putting test wrappers there fits its purpose. Concretely:\n\n```yaml\n# autopilot/.github/workflows/act-step-runner.yml\nname: Act Step Runner\n\non:\n  workflow_call:\n    inputs:\n      workflow:    { required: false, type: string }\n      step_id:     { required: false, type: string }\n      inputs_json: { required: false, type: string, default: '{}' }\n      artifact_path: { required: false, type: string, default: /tmp/act-artifacts }\n      image_repo:  { required: false, type: string, default: ghcr.io/clockwork-pilot/autopilot-ws }\n\njobs:\n  # Generic dispatcher \u2014 unchanged, keeps working for all reusable-workflow jobs\n  executor:\n    if: inputs.workflow != ''\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@de0fac2e4500dabe0009e67214ff5f5447ce83dd\n      - run: bash .github/scripts/act-step-dispatch.sh \"${{ inputs.workflow }}\" \"${{ inputs.step_id }}\" --inputs '${{ inputs.inputs_json }}' --artifact-server-path \"${{ inputs.artifact_path }}\"\n\n  # Composite-action wrappers \u2014 one per composite action you want testable\n  image-digest:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    outputs:\n      digest: ${{ steps.d.outputs.digest }}\n      image:  ${{ steps.d.outputs.image }}\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@de0fac2e4500dabe0009e67214ff5f5447ce83dd\n      - id: d\n        uses: ./.github/actions/image-digest\n        with: { image_repo: ${{ inputs.image_repo }} }\n      - run: |\n          echo \"${{ steps.d.outputs.digest }}\" > /tmp/digest.txt\n          echo \"${{ steps.d.outputs.image }}\"  > /tmp/image.txt\n      - uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4\n        with: { name: image-digest, path: /tmp/digest.txt }\n```\n\nTest invocation becomes:\n```bash\n# composite action, via the in-file wrapper\nact workflow_call -W .github/workflows/act-step-runner.yml \\\n    -j image-digest --input image_repo=ghcr.io/...\n\n# existing reusable-workflow job, via generic executor (unchanged)\nact workflow_call -W .github/workflows/act-step-runner.yml \\\n    -j executor --input workflow=coding-agent.yml --input step_id=parse-issue\n```\n\nWorks, and here's the honest tradeoff:\n\n**Upside.** No per-action test file. File count stays flat. Test wrappers live next to the thing that runs them (the dispatcher), which is arguably *more* discoverable than a scatter of `*-test.yml` files.\n\n**Downside.** Mixed-concern file. `act-step-runner.yml` stops being a pure generic dispatcher and becomes \"dispatcher + registry of composite-action test wrappers.\" As you add composite actions, the file grows with `jobs.<composite-name>` stanzas. At some point you'll want to split them back out \u2014 but that's a refactor you can do when it hurts, not preemptively.\n\n**Gotchas.**\n- The `if: inputs.workflow != ''` guard on `executor` is important \u2014 otherwise `act -j image-digest` would also try to run `executor` with empty inputs, which your dispatch script probably doesn't handle gracefully.\n- Job ids in `act-step-runner.yml` must not collide with job ids in the workflows it dispatches to \u2014 which they won't, because the wrappers use the composite action's name (`image-digest`) rather than inner job names (`fetch-manifest`, `parse-digest`).\n- If you ever want to test the composite action under different input combinations, each is another `act -j image-digest --input ...` invocation with different args \u2014 you don't need multiple wrapper jobs unless the setup differs.\n\n**Recommendation.** Do it. Start with image-digest as the first composite-action wrapper in `act-step-runner.yml`. If the file grows past ~5 wrapper jobs or gets complicated, split per-action test files at that point. Keeping it in one file now is the right call \u2014 it's pre-consolidation, not technical debt."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
