{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T13:42:03.482049", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Yes. A test job is the mechanism \u2014 because `act` can only target *jobs*, and composite actions aren't jobs. So to test a composite action, you need a thin job whose steps just call the action and surface its outputs. That's the wrapper.\n\nShape of the wrapper:\n\n```yaml\njobs:\n  image-digest:                      # the test job\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    outputs:\n      digest: ${{ steps.d.outputs.digest }}\n      image:  ${{ steps.d.outputs.image }}\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@...\n      - id: d\n        uses: ./.github/actions/image-digest     # the thing under test\n        with:\n          image_repo: ${{ inputs.image_repo }}\n      - run: |\n          echo \"${{ steps.d.outputs.digest }}\" > /tmp/digest.txt\n      - uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4\n        with: { name: image-digest, path: /tmp/digest.txt }\n```\n\nThree roles this job plays:\n\n1. **Callable entry point.** `act -j image-digest` targets a job \u2014 the action alone isn't targetable.\n2. **Input forwarder.** Takes `inputs.image_repo` from the workflow and passes it to the action as `with:`.\n3. **Output capture.** Surfaces `steps.d.outputs.*` as either job-level `outputs:` (for programmatic assertions via the existing harness) or artifacts (for inspection), or both.\n\nIt's a harness job, not a production job. Don't call it from real workflows. Its only consumers are `act` invocations (and optionally a GitHub-hosted test workflow running the same file against `workflow_dispatch`).\n\nWhere it lives: inside `act-step-runner.yml`, as we just discussed \u2014 one such job per composite action you want to cover. Or in per-action `*-test.yml` files if the collection grows. Same job pattern either way.\n\nExisting job-testing in autopilot (the `fetch-manifest`, `parse-digest` jobs in `image-digest.yml`) already worked like this implicitly: `act -j fetch-manifest` ran the job, captured outputs. The only difference with composite actions is that the job no longer *contains* the logic \u2014 it *wraps* the logic, which lives in a separate action file. Mechanically identical from the test harness's perspective."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
