{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T15:18:52.469529", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace/autopilot", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "explain         \"run_agent_is_self_hosted\": {\n          \"id\": \"run_agent_is_self_hosted\",\n          \"cmd\": \"yq -r '.jobs[\\\"run-agent\\\"].\\\"runs-on\\\" | .[]' $PROJECT_ROOT/.github/workflows/coding-agent.yml | grep -qx self-hosted\",\n          \"description\": \"Structural: run-agent must include the self-hosted label in runs-on. The agent executes untrusted code; running it on a shared ubuntu-latest runner would co-locate that code with other GitHub-hosted jobs and violate the isolation model the PAT scoping depends on.\",\n          \"fails_count\": 1\n        }", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-23T15:19:23.341700", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/52dd771c-b9eb-4144-8085-1b2d99eb1964.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace/autopilot", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "**What it checks:** The `run-agent` job in `coding-agent.yml` must declare `self-hosted` as one of its `runs-on` labels.\n\n**The command, piece by piece:**\n\n```bash\nyq -r '.jobs[\"run-agent\"].\"runs-on\" | .[]' $PROJECT_ROOT/.github/workflows/coding-agent.yml \\\n  | grep -qx self-hosted\n```\n\n1. `yq -r '.jobs[\"run-agent\"].\"runs-on\"'` \u2014 extracts the `runs-on:` value from the `run-agent` job. In `coding-agent.yml` it looks like:\n   ```yaml\n   run-agent:\n     runs-on: [self-hosted, \"${{ inputs.runner_label }}\"]\n   ```\n2. `| .[]` \u2014 iterates the array, printing each label on its own line (`self-hosted`, then `${{ ... }}`).\n3. `| grep -qx self-hosted` \u2014 `-q` silent, `-x` full-line match. Succeeds (exit 0) only if one of those labels is exactly `self-hosted`.\n\nSo the cmd exits 0 when `self-hosted` appears in the array, non-zero otherwise.\n\n**Why this matters (from the description):**\n\n`run-agent` is the job that executes the LLM-driven agent inside Docker. That agent runs whatever code the issue body tells it to \u2014 effectively untrusted. GitHub-hosted runners (`ubuntu-latest` et al.) are shared pools: a compromised step on one job could, in principle, observe or influence state on other jobs sharing the runner image / network. The isolation model for autopilot assumes:\n\n- The agent runs on a **self-hosted** runner you control.\n- `UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN` and other secrets are only exposed to jobs running in that isolated environment.\n- The `runner_label` input (usually a username) selects *which* self-hosted runner.\n\nIf someone changed `runs-on` to `ubuntu-latest` for \"convenience,\" the PAT-scoping story would break: secrets would travel into a GitHub-hosted sandbox, the agent would have network access to GitHub's default egress paths, and one selftest's runtime could leak into another caller's. This constraint is a tripwire that fails CI the moment that drift is introduced.\n\n**Failure modes it catches:**\n\n| Change | Detected? |\n|---|---|\n| `runs-on: ubuntu-latest` | \u2705 no `self-hosted` in output |\n| `runs-on: [ubuntu-latest, self-hosted]` | \u274c passes (still includes self-hosted \u2014 probably fine since that's also what happens in the current config) |\n| `runs-on: ${{ matrix.runner }}` with matrix including `ubuntu-latest` | \u274c not caught \u2014 yq sees a single expression string, not an array |\n| Removing `runs-on:` entirely | \u2705 yq returns null, grep fails |\n\n**Limitation:** The constraint doesn't check *only* `self-hosted` is present \u2014 it checks `self-hosted` is *among* the labels. A multi-label `[self-hosted, ubuntu-latest]` would pass, which is a false-negative worth noting. If you wanted strict enforcement (\"no GitHub-hosted labels allowed\"), you'd add a second constraint that negates against a list like `ubuntu-latest|windows-latest|macos-latest`."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
