{"timestamp": "2026-04-24T01:19:42.231610", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "cd29e658-61da-4c2d-8626-aa2fbdd1bddb", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/cd29e658-61da-4c2d-8626-aa2fbdd1bddb.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Answer to your question: the action does **not** apply the per-spec envs itself \u2014 it just runs `check_spec_constraints.py` (no args, no env passthrough). The envs (`PROJECT_ROOT=autopilot`) are meant to be consumed by the Python tool when it iterates specs from `project.k.json`. Our wrapper doesn't touch them.\n\nSo the error `spec not found: /workspace/autopilot/spec.k.json` is **not** an env-forwarding issue. The tool correctly resolved spec_dir `autopilot` \u2192 `/workspace/autopilot/spec.k.json`. That file is absent at runtime because:\n\n- `project.k.json` declares a spec at `autopilot/` (the submodule)\n- The library reusable workflow's `actions/checkout` does **not** pass `submodules: true`\n- So in CI, `autopilot/` is the empty submodule dir \u2192 `autopilot/spec.k.json` missing \u2192 error\n\nTwo places this can be fixed:\n\n1. **Selftest side**: caller can't inject `submodules: true` into the reusable workflow \u2014 the reusable owns the checkout step. So the reusable must expose it.\n2. **Library side** (`autopilot/.github/workflows/check-constraints.yml`): add a `submodules` input (default `false`) forwarded into `actions/checkout`.\n\nWant me to add the `submodules` input to the library workflow and set it to `true` from selftest?"}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
