{"timestamp": "2026-04-24T09:33:58.443277", "event": "Stop", "status": "blocked", "reason": "Constraint checks failed", "recurring_failures": [], "data": {"session_id": "b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "## Report: `uses_marketplace_workflow` constraint failure\n\n### What the constraint checks\nFor every `.yml` in `.github/workflows/`, it requires a line matching:\n```\nuses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/<name>.yml@<ref>\n```\ni.e. each workflow must *call a reusable workflow* from the `Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot` marketplace repo.\n\n### Why it's failing\n`check-constraints.yml` currently calls a **composite action**, not a reusable workflow:\n```yaml\n- uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/actions/check-constraints@main\n```\nTwo mismatches vs. the regex:\n1. Path is `.github/actions/...` not `.github/workflows/...`.\n2. It's a `steps:`-level `uses:` (composite action), not a job-level `uses:` (reusable workflow).\n\nThe last few commits (`cddde57`, `e073b4b`) deliberately switched *away* from the reusable workflow to the composite action so the consumer could own the `checkout` step and pass `submodules: recursive` \u2014 needed because `project.k.json` points at the `autopilot/` submodule.\n\n### Why this is a real conflict\n- **Constraint demands:** job-level `uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/*.yml@<ref>` (reusable workflow shape).\n- **Current need:** consumer-side `actions/checkout@\u2026 with submodules: recursive` before the check runs. Reusable workflows can't have steps injected before them by the caller \u2014 they do their own checkout internally.\n\nSo either the reusable workflow must learn to handle submodules, or the consumer must go back to calling it and live with whatever checkout behavior it does.\n\n### Options\n\n**Option A \u2014 Call the reusable workflow and pass a submodules input**\nRequires `Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/check-constraints.yml` to accept a `submodules` input (e.g. `submodules: recursive`) and pass it to its internal `actions/checkout`. Then here:\n```yaml\njobs:\n  check-constraints:\n    uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/check-constraints.yml@main\n    with:\n      submodules: recursive\n```\nCleanest, but needs a change in the upstream autopilot repo (and a version bump).\n\n**Option B \u2014 Call the reusable workflow as-is, move submodule handling inside it**\nIf the upstream reusable workflow already does `submodules: recursive` (or we update it to), the consumer just calls it with no inputs. Same upstream change required.\n\n**Option C \u2014 Two jobs: a no-op caller + the real composite step**\nAdd a second workflow file (or a second job) that satisfies the constraint by calling *some* reusable workflow from `Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/*.yml@\u2026`, while keeping the composite-action job for the actual submodule-aware check. Satisfies the regex but is cosmetic/ugly \u2014 the constraint scans *every* workflow file, so every file must contain the `uses:` line. That means the current file still fails. Doesn't actually work unless the line is added to *this* file too.\n\n**Option D \u2014 Hybrid: reusable workflow that delegates, plus caller owns checkout**\nNot possible in GitHub Actions \u2014 a job that uses `uses: <reusable>` can't also have `steps:`. So you can't mix consumer-side checkout with a reusable-workflow call in one job.\n\n### Recommendation\n**Option A.** Update the upstream `Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot` reusable workflow to accept a `submodules` input, then revert this file to calling it. That's the only option that genuinely satisfies the constraint across every workflow file while preserving submodule support.\n\nWant me to proceed with Option A (assuming the upstream workflow supports, or will support, a `submodules` input)?"}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
