{"timestamp": "2026-04-24T10:33:27.565467", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "so will our marketplace workflows.actions trigger coding-agent for private repos with self-hosted runner?", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-24T10:34:05.635586", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Yes \u2014 the design explicitly supports private repos with self-hosted runners. Here's the shape:\n\n### How runner selection works\n- **`coding-agent.yml`** (the heavy-lift reusable workflow) splits jobs:\n  - The agent execution jobs (lines 168, 219) run on `runs-on: [self-hosted, \"${{ inputs.runner_label }}\"]` \u2014 they land on your own runner.\n  - Orchestration jobs (checkout, parse, PR open, comment) use `ubuntu-latest` (GitHub-hosted).\n- `runner_label` is a workflow input; the consumer passes it through.\n- **`issue-trigger.yml`** sets `runner_label = github.event.sender.login` \u2014 the GitHub username of whoever applied the label. So each user's issue is routed to the runner labeled with their username.\n\n### What this requires in a private repo\n1. **A self-hosted runner online**, registered with the label `<username>` (matching the person who will apply the trigger label). `issue-trigger.yml` pre-flights this via the GitHub API using `RUNNERS_PAT` \u2014 if no online runner with that label exists, it fails fast instead of queuing forever.\n2. **`RUNNERS_PAT` secret** \u2014 fine-grained PAT with `Administration: Read-only` on the consumer repo (needed for the runner existence check). Private-repo only distinction: nothing special, same PAT scope as public.\n3. **A consumer workflow_dispatch caller** (e.g. `autopilot-selftest`'s own `coding-agent.yml`) that accepts `runner_label` + `issue_number` inputs and calls `Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/coding-agent.yml@<ref>`. Its filename goes to `issue-trigger.yml`'s `target_workflow` input.\n4. **GitHub Actions enabled** for the private repo, with permission for workflows to dispatch other workflows (default on). Private repos consume Actions minutes for the `ubuntu-latest` orchestration jobs; only the agent jobs run off your self-hosted capacity.\n\n### Gotchas specific to private + self-hosted\n- GitHub **strongly discourages self-hosted runners on public repos** (fork-PR code execution risk). On **private** repos this is the intended config \u2014 no warning applies.\n- The runner's label must match the sender's GitHub username **exactly** (case-sensitive). Users without a matching runner will trigger the pre-flight failure.\n- `actions/checkout` in the agent jobs will use the auto-provided `GITHUB_TOKEN`; private-repo checkout works fine as long as workflow permissions allow `contents: read` (default). For `merge_into_upstream`, a separate PAT (`upstream_pr_token` input) is needed.\n- If the self-hosted runner is ephemeral/containerized, make sure submodules/tooling required by `coding-agent.yml` steps are present \u2014 nothing in the workflow installs a base toolchain on the runner.\n\n### Short answer\nIf (a) a self-hosted runner labeled with the triggering user's GitHub login is online, (b) `RUNNERS_PAT` is configured, and (c) a thin consumer wrapper workflow exists calling `coding-agent.yml`, then yes \u2014 labeling an issue on the private repo will dispatch coding-agent onto that self-hosted runner."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
