{"timestamp": "2026-04-24T15:06:19.249641", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Categorized brainstorm, ~30 candidates:\n\n### Prepare / Ready (covers both pull-and-build modes)\n1. `prepare-docker-image` \u2014 my pick; neutral; matches the job name it replaces.\n2. `ready-docker-image` \u2014 emphasizes the outcome (\"image is ready\").\n3. `stage-docker-image` \u2014 deployment-flavor; implies \"get it in place for the next step\".\n4. `provision-docker-image` \u2014 infra vocab; fits IaC-ish vibes.\n5. `setup-docker-image` \u2014 familiar, but overused in action names.\n\n### Resolve / Acquire (emphasizes \"figure out what image to use\")\n6. `resolve-docker-image` \u2014 good for the \"either pull or build\" duality.\n7. `acquire-docker-image` \u2014 slightly formal.\n8. `obtain-docker-image` \u2014 ditto.\n9. `fetch-docker-image` \u2014 misleads toward pull-only.\n10. `get-docker-image` \u2014 too generic; collides with every GH action ever.\n\n### Derive / Extend (emphasizes layering on a base)\n11. `derive-docker-image` \u2014 accurate when Dockerfile is set, odd when not.\n12. `extend-docker-image` \u2014 same caveat.\n13. `layer-docker-image` \u2014 concrete; Buildx-adjacent.\n14. `overlay-docker-image` \u2014 filesystem connotation; could mislead.\n15. `compose-docker-image` \u2014 collides with `docker compose`; skip.\n\n### Ensure / Materialize (idempotency angle)\n16. `ensure-docker-image` \u2014 clean; implies \"make it exist, whatever it takes\".\n17. `materialize-docker-image` \u2014 precise but heavy.\n18. `realize-docker-image` \u2014 literary; unusual for CI.\n\n### Cache / Warm (caching as the headline feature)\n19. `cached-docker-image` \u2014 adjective-first is awkward as an action name.\n20. `cache-docker-image` \u2014 reads as \"put it in the cache\", not \"pull+build+cache\".\n21. `warm-docker-image` \u2014 \"warm the cache\"; cute, imprecise.\n22. `prime-docker-image` \u2014 similar.\n\n### Build-adjacent (if you don't mind the \"build\" verb despite also pulling)\n23. `build-or-pull-docker-image` \u2014 self-documenting; verbose.\n24. `buildx-docker-image` \u2014 ties to Buildx explicitly; narrows the brand.\n25. `docker-image-builder` \u2014 noun form.\n\n### Domain-flavor nouns\n26. `docker-image-factory` \u2014 produces images on demand.\n27. `docker-image-forge` \u2014 same, more metal.\n28. `docker-image-kit` \u2014 toolset connotation.\n29. `docker-image-harness` \u2014 scaffolding connotation.\n\n### Compound / descriptive\n30. `runnable-docker-image` \u2014 emphasizes the post-condition (you can `docker run` the output).\n31. `pin-docker-image` \u2014 fixes it to a content-hashed tag (accurate!); may collide with \"pin dependencies\" phrasing.\n\n### My short list (if I had to pick 3)\n- **`prepare-docker-image`** \u2014 broadest fit; reads right in both modes; zero jargon.\n- **`resolve-docker-image`** \u2014 best captures the \"give me a tag, I don't care how\" contract.\n- **`ensure-docker-image`** \u2014 best captures the idempotency (fast-path skip when tag exists).\n\nWhich family resonates?"}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
