{"timestamp": "2026-04-24T15:12:45.575096", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Structural reason, not an oversight: `agent.yml` is a **caller of a reusable workflow**, not a step-level composition.\n\n```yaml\njobs:\n  run:\n    uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/coding-agent.yml@main   # job-level\n```\n\nA job that uses `uses: <reusable-workflow>` cannot also have `steps:` \u2014 it's one or the other. So you can't put an `ensure-docker-image` step \"before\" it in this file. The image-prep step lives inside the `prepare-image` **job** of `coding-agent.yml`, which is already the correct home for it (runs on the self-hosted runner, feeds `run-agent`).\n\nContrast with the selftest's `check-constraints.yml`: that file intentionally **bypasses** the reusable shim (`check-constraints.yml` in autopilot) and calls composite actions at the step level \u2014 precisely because it needs to own the checkout step (`submodules: recursive`). Step-level = visible steps. Job-level reusable-workflow = one line, sub-steps hidden inside the called workflow.\n\n### When you'd split the agent caller like the check caller\n\nIf you ever wanted the selftest to own checkout or pre-agent setup (e.g. login to a private registry before `ensure-docker-image` pulls from it, or set up auth), you'd have to:\n\n1. Stop calling `coding-agent.yml` as a reusable workflow.\n2. Inline the constituent jobs (fetch-issue, parse-issue, validate-runner, prepare-image, run-agent, open-pr, \u2026).\n3. Wire `ensure-docker-image` + `run-agent` as sibling steps inside `prepare-image`.\n\nThat's a big surface to own. Not worth it unless you need pre-pull auth or similar. Today, nothing in the agent flow needs consumer-owned setup before image prep \u2014 `ensure-docker-image` runs on the self-hosted runner and pulls from a public registry, so the reusable-workflow one-liner is the right shape.\n\n### Where the \"separate step\" actually lives\nInside `autopilot/.github/workflows/coding-agent.yml`:\n\n```yaml\nprepare-image:\n  needs: [validate-runner, image-digest]\n  runs-on: [self-hosted, \"${{ inputs.runner_label }}\"]\n  outputs:\n    image: ${{ steps.image.outputs.image }}\n  steps:\n    - if: inputs.dockerfile != ''\n      uses: actions/checkout@...\n    - id: image\n      uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/actions/ensure-docker-image@main\n      with: { ... }\n```\n\nThe step is there \u2014 it's just one level of indirection away from `agent.yml`. The consumer's run log will show `prepare-image` as a distinct job with `Ensure Docker Image` as its step, same legibility as the check flow's two-step shape."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-24T15:14:07.900835", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "can't we make an action from this? uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/coding-agent.yml@main", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-24T15:14:50.712552", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Short answer: **no, not cleanly.** Composite actions are single-job; `coding-agent.yml` is fundamentally multi-job. Converting it would force you to give up things that are load-bearing.\n\n### Why reusable-workflow, not composite action\n\nComposite actions run in the **caller's job**, on the caller's single runner, with the caller's permissions. They're a sequence of steps. Reusable workflows are whole workflows with their own job DAG, multiple `runs-on` targets, per-job permissions, and per-job environments.\n\n`coding-agent.yml` depends on all four of those:\n\n| Feature | Used where | Composite-action blocker |\n|---|---|---|\n| Multiple `runs-on` | `fetch-issue` / `parse-issue` / `open-pr` on `ubuntu-latest`; `prepare-image` / `run-agent` on `[self-hosted, <label>]` | Composite inherits caller's single runner \u2014 can't split light orchestration from self-hosted agent execution |\n| Per-job `environment:` | `open-upstream-pr` uses `environment: upstream-pr` so `UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN` is only in scope for that one job and only on branches that match the env's deployment rules | Composite actions have no concept of environments \u2014 secret would be in scope for the entire action, including the self-hosted agent container |\n| Per-job `permissions:` | `run-agent: contents: write`; `open-pr: pull-requests: write, issues: write`; `open-upstream-pr: contents: read, issues: write` | Composite inherits one permission block from the caller \u2014 every step gets the union |\n| `secrets:` block at `workflow_call` | Caller passes `UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN` as a named secret | Composite actions take secrets as `inputs:` \u2014 they're passed as plain env vars and lose some of the native secret handling |\n| `needs:` DAG across runners | `open-upstream-pr` needs `run-agent` results but runs on a different runner in a different environment | Composite actions are linear-step, not a DAG |\n\nThe upstream-pr environment isolation in particular is the hard-stop. The whole point of it is that `UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN` never enters the self-hosted runner where arbitrary LLM-driven code executes. Collapsing the workflow into a composite action breaks that \u2014 the token becomes available anywhere inside the action.\n\n### What *is* possible\n\nThe pieces already split correctly:\n\n- **Composite actions** own single-responsibility units: `parse-issue`, `choose-branch`, `parse-digest`, `ensure-docker-image`, `create-pr`, `comment-agent-result`, `check-constraints`. Each runs on whichever runner its caller job chooses, inherits its permissions.\n- **Reusable workflows** own orchestrations that cross runners / environments / permissions: `coding-agent.yml`, `check-constraints.yml`, `image-digest.yml`.\n\nThe consumer-side experience is fine:\n\n```yaml\n# agent.yml \u2014 stays a one-liner at job level:\njobs:\n  run:\n    uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/coding-agent.yml@main\n    with: { ... }\n    secrets: { ... }\n```\n\nThe consumer doesn't *want* step-level control here. They'd have to reconstruct nine jobs, cross-runner handoffs, and environment-scoped secrets themselves. The reusable workflow is the correct form of encapsulation for this surface.\n\n### If you really wanted step-level\n\nYou'd have two meaningful halves:\n\n1. **`prepare-and-run-agent`** composite action \u2014 `ensure-docker-image` + run-in-docker. Self-hosted only. No secrets.\n2. **`open-agent-pr`** composite action \u2014 PR creation + comment. Ubuntu-latest.\n\nA consumer then owns two jobs in their caller workflow, wires the cross-runner handoff themselves (upload-artifact \u2192 download-artifact for the agent's outputs), owns the upstream-pr environment gate themselves. That's fine as an advanced escape hatch but worse as the default \u2014 more for the consumer to get right.\n\n### Recommendation\n\nKeep `coding-agent.yml` as a reusable workflow. The \"why it isn't a composite action\" question has a clean answer: **multi-runner + environment isolation + per-job permissions**, any one of which alone would block it."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
