{"timestamp": "2026-04-24T15:32:36.630910", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "why not wrap all these action to another high level action?", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-24T15:33:11.931884", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Same wall, different angle. A \"high-level wrapping action\" doesn't escape the composite-action constraints \u2014 it just moves where they bite.\n\n### Why nesting composite actions doesn't help\n\nA composite action that calls other composite actions still runs in **one job, on one runner, with one permission set, with no environment**. Nesting changes nothing about the envelope:\n\n```yaml\n# \"high-level\" wrapper \u2014 still runs in caller's single job\nruns:\n  using: composite\n  steps:\n    - uses: ./actions/run-agent          # this step runs on caller's runner\n    - uses: ./actions/open-agent-pr      # so does this one\n    - uses: ./actions/open-upstream-pr   # and this one\n```\n\nThe four blockers carry through unchanged:\n\n| Blocker | Why nesting doesn't fix it |\n|---|---|\n| `run-agent` needs self-hosted, `open-agent-pr` needs ubuntu-latest | The outer action has one `runs-on` \u2014 whichever the caller picked. Can't switch mid-action. |\n| `open-upstream-pr` needs `environment: upstream-pr` for secret isolation | Composite actions can't declare environments at all, nested or not. |\n| `run-agent` wants `contents: write`, `open-pr` wants `pull-requests: write`, `open-upstream-pr` wants the upstream PAT scoped only there | Single permission block for the whole composite. |\n| `secrets:` block with `UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN` only flowing to `open-upstream-pr` | Composite actions take secrets as plain inputs \u2014 same env for every nested action. |\n\n### Concrete failure\n\nIf you wrapped everything into `autopilot-do-everything` composite and the consumer put it in one job:\n\n```yaml\njobs:\n  agent:\n    runs-on: [self-hosted, \"${{ inputs.runner_label }}\"]   # forced choice\n    steps:\n      - uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/actions/autopilot-do-everything@main\n```\n\n- `open-agent-pr`'s `gh` calls run on the self-hosted runner instead of ubuntu-latest. Fine, but wastes self-hosted capacity for trivial API calls.\n- `UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN` passed as input is now an env var **inside the self-hosted runner**, visible to the LLM execution container. That's the security property the current design explicitly protects.\n- The consumer can't set `environment: upstream-pr` only for the PR-open phase \u2014 either the whole job is gated (which means the agent can't run without env approval) or none of it is.\n\n### What a \"high-level wrapper\" actually is\n\nThe only type of wrapper that can cross runners, scope secrets per phase, and split permissions is a **reusable workflow** \u2014 which is exactly `coding-agent.yml`. It *is* the high-level wrapper. It's written in the only form of YAML that has the expressive power to compose jobs with those properties.\n\nSo the mental model should be:\n\n- **Composite actions** = single-job building blocks. `ensure-docker-image`, `parse-issue`, `choose-branch`, `create-pr`, `run-agent` (proposed), `open-agent-pr` (proposed).\n- **Reusable workflows** = multi-job compositions of those blocks. `coding-agent.yml`, `check-constraints.yml`, `image-digest.yml`.\n\nCalling a reusable workflow from a reusable workflow is allowed and cheap \u2014 so if you want a higher-level orchestrator (e.g., `coding-agent-with-rollback.yml` that calls `coding-agent.yml` then a cleanup workflow), that composes at the workflow layer. But you never climb from composite actions back up to multi-runner \u2014 that path doesn't exist in GitHub Actions.\n\n### The short version\n\n\"High-level action that wraps multi-runner behavior\" is a thing GitHub Actions doesn't have. The nearest thing is a high-level reusable workflow, and we already have one \u2014 calling it from the consumer's caller is the 8-line `uses:` at job level."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
