{"timestamp": "2026-04-24T15:37:10.904919", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Yes, that's Option 2 from earlier. It's mechanically sound *with a subtle point*: the two workflows don't actually \"share\" the image \u2014 they compute the same content-hashed tag, and the second call hits `ensure-docker-image`'s fast-path instead of re-running work.\n\n### The mechanics\n\n```yaml\n# autopilot/.github/workflows/ensure-docker-image.yml  (new)\non:\n  workflow_call:\n    inputs:\n      runner_label:     { required: true, type: string }\n      base_image:       { required: true, type: string }\n      dockerfile:       { required: false, type: string, default: \"\" }\n      build_args:       { required: false, type: string, default: \"\" }\n      cache_key_prefix: { required: true, type: string }\n    outputs:\n      image:\n        value: ${{ jobs.ensure.outputs.image }}\n\njobs:\n  ensure:\n    runs-on: [self-hosted, \"${{ inputs.runner_label }}\"]\n    outputs:\n      image: ${{ steps.e.outputs.image }}\n    steps:\n      - if: inputs.dockerfile != ''\n        uses: actions/checkout@...\n      - id: e\n        uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/actions/ensure-docker-image@main\n        with:\n          base_image:       ${{ inputs.base_image }}\n          dockerfile:       ${{ inputs.dockerfile }}\n          build_args:       ${{ inputs.build_args }}\n          tag:              autopilot-agent\n          cache_key_prefix: ${{ inputs.cache_key_prefix }}\n```\n\n```yaml\n# autopilot-selftest/.github/workflows/agent.yml\njobs:\n  image:\n    uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/ensure-docker-image.yml@main\n    with:\n      runner_label:     ${{ inputs.runner_label }}\n      base_image:       ghcr.io/clockwork-pilot/autopilot-ws:latest\n      dockerfile:       Dockerfile.agent-sample\n      cache_key_prefix: ${{ github.repository }}-agent-img\n\n  run:\n    needs: image\n    uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/coding-agent.yml@main\n    with:\n      runner_label:     ${{ inputs.runner_label }}\n      issue_number:     ${{ inputs.issue_number }}\n      dockerfile:       Dockerfile.agent-sample                   # <-- duplicated\n      cache_key_prefix: ${{ github.repository }}-agent-img        # <-- duplicated\n    secrets:\n      UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN }}\n```\n\n### What actually happens at runtime\n\n1. Job `image` runs on self-hosted runner X. `ensure-docker-image` builds `autopilot-agent:<prefix>-<hash>` locally. Outputs that tag.\n2. Job `run` hands off to `coding-agent.yml`. Its `prepare-image` job lands on self-hosted runner X (same label). Its internal `ensure-docker-image` call computes the **same** `<prefix>-<hash>` (same `dockerfile`, same `base_image`, same `cache_key_prefix`). `docker image inspect` finds the tag \u2192 fast-path skip.\n\nNet: the image is built exactly once, in the outer job. The inner call is a ~2-second no-op.\n\n### The gotchas\n\n1. **Same-runner assumption.** Both jobs must land on the literal same self-hosted runner (not just same-label). Works with single-user setups where one person = one runner. Breaks with a pool of runners sharing the label: job 1 builds on runner A, job 2 runs on runner B, fast-path misses, prepare-image rebuilds. Not *broken*, just duplicated work \u2014 but all the caller-side hoisting bought you nothing.\n\n2. **Caller-side duplication.** `dockerfile:` and `cache_key_prefix:` (and implicitly `base_image:`, which must match autopilot-ws:latest for the hashes to align) are specified in both `uses:` blocks. Drift between them means hash drift means two separate builds.\n\n3. **Doesn't simplify `coding-agent.yml`.** Its `prepare-image` still invokes `ensure-docker-image` internally. Removing that would break the path where no outer hoist happens (consumers who don't wrap). So you pay the cost of the internal step whether or not you also hoist it.\n\n4. **The `agent_image` input gets awkward.** If instead of hoisting *the same* `ensure-docker-image` call you tried to pass `needs.image.outputs.image` via `agent_image:`, the inner `ensure-docker-image` would treat it as a new `base_image` and try to `docker manifest inspect` / `docker pull` a purely-local tag \u2014 fails. So you can't use the `agent_image:` handoff; you must duplicate the inputs instead.\n\n### What this pattern actually buys\n\nHoisting is only worth it if the consumer wants to **do something between prep and agent run** that the reusable workflow doesn't expose:\n\n- **Approval gate**: put `environment: require-approval` on the `image` job so a reviewer signs off before the agent runs.\n- **Matrix**: prep multiple images in parallel, dispatch agent against each.\n- **Cron-then-dispatch**: prep on a schedule so first-run latency is amortized, agent runs on demand.\n- **Cross-job visibility of cache status**: the `image` job's output makes cache hit/miss a first-class signal in the run graph, visible without scrolling into `coding-agent.yml`'s `prepare-image`.\n\nIf none of those apply, the hoist is pure duplication \u2014 visible, but only in the caller file, not in the run log (the run log shows `prepare-image` regardless).\n\n### Honest recommendation\n\nShip `ensure-docker-image.yml` as a workflow-level wrapper **only if** you have a concrete use case for the four patterns above. Otherwise the current shape (consumer passes `dockerfile` to `coding-agent.yml`, the internal `prepare-image` job shows up in the run log) already delivers visibility without caller duplication.\n\nThe pattern is valid \u2014 it just mostly solves a problem you don't have."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
