{"timestamp": "2026-04-24T15:41:14.421632", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Yes \u2014 several ways. Cleanest is to have `ensure-docker-image.yml` **echo its inputs back as outputs**, then `coding-agent.yml` reads them via `needs.<job>.outputs`. Single source of truth, no caller-side duplication.\n\n### `ensure-docker-image.yml` adds echo outputs\n\n```yaml\n# autopilot/.github/workflows/ensure-docker-image.yml\non:\n  workflow_call:\n    inputs:\n      runner_label:     { required: true,  type: string }\n      base_image:       { required: true,  type: string }\n      dockerfile:       { required: false, type: string, default: \"\" }\n      build_args:       { required: false, type: string, default: \"\" }\n      cache_key_prefix: { required: true,  type: string }\n    outputs:\n      image:\n        value: ${{ jobs.ensure.outputs.image }}\n      # Echo inputs as outputs so the caller can pass them downstream verbatim.\n      dockerfile:\n        value: ${{ inputs.dockerfile }}\n      build_args:\n        value: ${{ inputs.build_args }}\n      cache_key_prefix:\n        value: ${{ inputs.cache_key_prefix }}\n      base_image:\n        value: ${{ inputs.base_image }}\n\njobs:\n  ensure:\n    runs-on: [self-hosted, \"${{ inputs.runner_label }}\"]\n    outputs:\n      image: ${{ steps.e.outputs.image }}\n    steps:\n      - if: inputs.dockerfile != ''\n        uses: actions/checkout@...\n      - id: e\n        uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/actions/ensure-docker-image@main\n        with:\n          base_image:       ${{ inputs.base_image }}\n          dockerfile:       ${{ inputs.dockerfile }}\n          build_args:       ${{ inputs.build_args }}\n          tag:              autopilot-agent\n          cache_key_prefix: ${{ inputs.cache_key_prefix }}\n```\n\nThe echo trick works because `outputs.<x>.value:` in `workflow_call` can reference the `inputs.` context directly \u2014 documented, no extra step needed.\n\n### Caller \u2014 values specified once\n\n```yaml\n# .github/workflows/agent.yml\njobs:\n  image:\n    uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/ensure-docker-image.yml@main\n    with:\n      runner_label:     ${{ inputs.runner_label }}\n      base_image:       ghcr.io/clockwork-pilot/autopilot-ws:latest\n      dockerfile:       Dockerfile.agent-sample                  # <-- only here\n      cache_key_prefix: ${{ github.repository }}-agent-img       # <-- only here\n\n  run:\n    needs: image\n    uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/coding-agent.yml@main\n    with:\n      runner_label:     ${{ inputs.runner_label }}\n      issue_number:     ${{ inputs.issue_number }}\n      dockerfile:       ${{ needs.image.outputs.dockerfile }}\n      cache_key_prefix: ${{ needs.image.outputs.cache_key_prefix }}\n    secrets:\n      UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN }}\n```\n\nZero duplication. Change `Dockerfile.agent-sample` once, both workflows see the new value.\n\n### Alternative: workflow-level `env`\n\nSimpler if you don't want to extend `ensure-docker-image.yml`'s output surface:\n\n```yaml\nenv:\n  AGENT_DOCKERFILE:       Dockerfile.agent-sample\n  AGENT_CACHE_KEY_PREFIX: ${{ github.repository }}-agent-img\n\njobs:\n  image:\n    uses: .../ensure-docker-image.yml@main\n    with:\n      dockerfile:       ${{ env.AGENT_DOCKERFILE }}\n      cache_key_prefix: ${{ env.AGENT_CACHE_KEY_PREFIX }}\n      ...\n\n  run:\n    needs: image\n    uses: .../coding-agent.yml@main\n    with:\n      dockerfile:       ${{ env.AGENT_DOCKERFILE }}\n      cache_key_prefix: ${{ env.AGENT_CACHE_KEY_PREFIX }}\n      ...\n```\n\nNote: `env.` in `jobs.<id>.with:` for a reusable-workflow call is allowed in most setups, but GitHub has historically had edge cases around context availability on reusable-workflow job definitions. The outputs-echo approach is bulletproof; env is terser but slightly riskier against future restrictions. I'd go with outputs.\n\n### Third alternative: a dedicated `config` job\n\nTrivially works, ugly:\n\n```yaml\njobs:\n  config:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    outputs:\n      dockerfile:       Dockerfile.agent-sample\n      cache_key_prefix: ${{ github.repository }}-agent-img\n    steps:\n      - run: ':'   # no-op \u2014 job needs at least one step\n```\n\nCosts one ubuntu-latest minute per run for a no-op. Skip unless you want runtime-dynamic config.\n\n### Recommendation\n\nUse the **outputs-echo** pattern. It composes naturally, declares the shared values in the workflow that owns them (`ensure-docker-image.yml` is the authority on what it built), and doesn't pay for an extra job. Only downside is `ensure-docker-image.yml`'s output list grows from 1 to 4 \u2014 fine."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
