ber }}", "+      docker_image: ${{ needs.image.outputs.docker_image }}", "     secrets:", "       UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN }}"]}], "originalFile": "name: Agent (with Dockerfile)\n\n# Companion to agent.yml: exercises the `dockerfile` input path through the\n# Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot coding-agent.yml reusable workflow, proving that\n# consumers can build a custom agent image (e.g. layering extra tooling on\n# top of autopilot-ws) and dispatch the agent against it.\n#\n# Like agent.yml, this is workflow_dispatch only \u2014 running it requires a\n# self-hosted runner labeled with your GitHub username and an issue_number\n# to act on. The sibling workflow (agent.yml) covers the default path with\n# no Dockerfile (base autopilot-ws as-is).\n\non:\n  workflow_dispatch:\n    inputs:\n      runner_label:\n        description: GitHub username (matches self-hosted runner label)\n        required: true\n        type: string\n      issue_number:\n        description: Issue number to work on\n        required: true\n        type: string\n\npermissions:\n  contents: write\n  pull-requests: write\n  issues: write\n\njobs:\n  run:\n    uses: Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/coding-agent.yml@main\n    with:\n      runner_label:     ${{ inputs.runner_label }}\n      issue_number:     ${{ inputs.issue_number }}\n      dockerfile:       Dockerfile.agent-sample\n      cache_key_prefix: ${{ github.repository }}-agent-img\n    secrets:\n      UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.UPSTREAM_PR_TOKEN }}\n", "userModified": false}, "tool_use_id": "toolu_015Bjoj4RAtJCfdHTq4VdtzJ", "duration_ms": 15}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-24T15:49:03.942570", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Done. Summary:\n\n### New reusable workflow\n- `autopilot/.github/workflows/ensure-docker-image.yml` \u2014 hoists `ensure-docker-image` to job level on self-hosted. Outputs `docker_image` (final local tag).\n\n### `coding-agent.yml` gains `docker_image:` input\n- When set: `prepare-image` short-circuits \u2014 one echo step, no internal build/pull.\n- When unset: falls back to the existing `ensure-docker-image` call (with `dockerfile`/`agent_image`/`cache_key_prefix`).\n- `cache_key_prefix` is now required only in the fallback path; a pre-flight step errors if it's missing when `docker_image` is unset.\n- Docstrings reflect the two modes.\n\n### Selftest callers rewritten to two-job shape\n- `.github/workflows/agent.yml` \u2014 default autopilot-ws case:\n  ```\n  jobs:\n    image: uses ensure-docker-image.yml   (no dockerfile)\n    run:   uses coding-agent.yml          (docker_image: needs.image.outputs.docker_image)\n  ```\n- `.github/workflows/agent-with-dockerfile.yml` \u2014 same shape but the `image` job passes `dockerfile: Dockerfile.agent-sample`.\n- Dockerfile and cache_key_prefix declared **once** per caller, in the `image` job. `coding-agent.yml` doesn't see them.\n\n### Validation\n- Constraints pass on both specs.\n- Selftest `uses_marketplace_autopilot` still satisfied (every workflow now references `Clockwork-Pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/*.yml@main` in at least one `uses:`).\n\n### Runtime behavior (same-runner case)\n1. `image` job: `ensure-docker-image` builds `autopilot-agent:<prefix>-<hash>` on runner X. Outputs ref.\n2. `run` job \u2192 `coding-agent.yml` \u2192 `prepare-image` lands on runner X, receives `docker_image`, echoes it (no build, no pull). `run-agent` consumes it.\n3. Image built exactly once, visible in the caller's run graph as the first job.\n\n### Known constraint\nBoth jobs must land on the same self-hosted runner (local tags don't cross daemons). Single-runner-per-label setups: fine. Pooled runners with shared labels: `run-agent` will fail fast with \"image not found\" \u2014 loud failure is the right signal to push to a registry instead."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-24T15:50:02.482414", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "should we specify something to enforce it?   Both jobs must land on the same self-hosted runner (local tags don't cross daemons). Single-runner-per-label setups: fine. Pooled runners with shared labels:         \n  run-agent will fail fast with \"image not found\" \u2014 loud failure is the right signal to push to a registry instead.", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-24T15:50:36.861370", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Three real options, ranging from \"document\" to \"engineer around\":\n\n### Option 1 \u2014 Preflight check with clear error message (cheap, ~5 lines)\n\nAdd a first step to `run-agent` (or `prepare-image` when `docker_image` is set) that inspects the tag locally and fails fast with a diagnostic instead of waiting for `docker run` to produce `Unable to find image`:\n\n```yaml\n- name: Verify pre-built image is on this runner\n  if: inputs.docker_image != ''\n  env:\n    DOCKER_IMAGE: ${{ inputs.docker_image }}\n  run: |\n    if ! docker image inspect \"$DOCKER_IMAGE\" >/dev/null 2>&1; then\n      echo \"::error::Pre-built image '$DOCKER_IMAGE' is not on this runner ($(hostname)).\n    The upstream ensure-docker-image.yml job built it on a different runner.\n    Fix: ensure runner_label maps to exactly one runner, or push the image\n    to a registry instead of passing a local tag.\"\n      exit 1\n    fi\n```\n\n**Pros**: zero infra cost, actionable error. **Cons**: detects, doesn't prevent.\n\n### Option 2 \u2014 Pin both jobs to the **same named runner** via runner.name as a label\n\nGitHub Actions runners accept custom labels at registration time. If each self-hosted runner is registered with its own hostname as an extra label (e.g. `--labels ${username},${hostname}`), the caller can capture it from job 1 and constrain job 2:\n\n```yaml\njobs:\n  image:\n    uses: .../ensure-docker-image.yml@main\n    with:\n      runner_label: ${{ inputs.runner_label }}\n      ...\n    # ensure-docker-image.yml exports an additional `runner_name` output\n    # by running: echo \"runner_name=${{ runner.name }}\" >> $GITHUB_OUTPUT\n\n  run:\n    needs: image\n    uses: .../coding-agent.yml@main\n    with:\n      runner_label: ${{ inputs.runner_label }}\n      runner_name:  ${{ needs.image.outputs.runner_name }}   # NEW\n      docker_image: ${{ needs.image.outputs.docker_image }}\n```\n\n`coding-agent.yml` then uses `runs-on: [self-hosted, \"${{ inputs.runner_label }}\", \"${{ inputs.runner_name }}\"]` on the self-hosted jobs, guaranteeing they land on the same machine.\n\n**Pros**: actually enforces co-location. Works with pooled setups. **Cons**: requires one-time runner-side config (add `--labels <hostname>` or similar to the ansible playbook). Needs plumbing through both reusable workflows.\n\n### Option 3 \u2014 Push to a registry (removes the constraint)\n\nAdd `push_to:` input to `ensure-docker-image.yml`: when set, tag + `docker push` to the registry after build. Output becomes the registry ref. `coding-agent.yml` then pulls on the downstream runner \u2014 works across any topology.\n\n**Pros**: topology-agnostic; survives runner churn; image becomes a first-class artifact. **Cons**: registry write auth required (PAT or `GITHUB_TOKEN` with `packages: write`); bandwidth cost per run; mutates the caching story (registry round-trip even on cache hit).\n\n### My recommendation\n\n**Do Option 1 now** (preflight check) \u2014 it costs nothing and turns a cryptic docker error into a clear \"fix your setup\" message. Ship it immediately.\n\n**Offer Option 2 as an input** for users who need enforcement. The ansible playbook can be updated to add `--labels ${RUNNER_HOSTNAME}` and both reusable workflows gain a `runner_name` input/output. Clean when the user opts in, invisible when they don't.\n\n**Document Option 3** as the escape hatch for pooled runners. Don't implement yet \u2014 wait for a consumer who actually has a pool. Pushing to a registry changes the performance/cost profile enough that it shouldn't be the default.\n\nWant me to implement Option 1 (preflight + friendly error)?"}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
