{"timestamp": "2026-04-24T15:53:22.060407", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Yes, with important small print.\n\n### The \"100%\" cases\nWith one self-hosted runner labeled `<username>` and a persistent docker install (what the ansible playbook sets up):\n\n- **Idle runner** \u2014 both jobs land on it, local tag visible, works.\n- **Busy runner** \u2014 `run` job queues until free, runs on the same machine, image is still there, works.\n- **Concurrent agent workflows** \u2014 both use the same content-hashed tag (same Dockerfile \u2192 same hash); second build is a fast-path hit; both consume the same image, works.\n- **Workflow cancelled / failed mid-run** \u2014 `needs: image` gates `run`; if `image` doesn't finish, `run` doesn't start. No dangling-reference failures.\n\n### Small print \u2014 edge cases that could break it\n\nNone of these are about \"runner pool vs single\"; they're about runner state:\n\n1. **Docker daemon storage wiped between the two jobs** \u2014 e.g. an admin runs `docker system prune -af`, or the runner is redeployed from an image mid-workflow, or a cron reimages the VM. Rare on a hand-installed runner; common on cloud/ephemeral setups. If you're not running prune jobs, fine.\n\n2. **Disk full \u2192 automatic image GC** \u2014 docker doesn't auto-GC, but some runner platforms do (GitHub-hosted is the extreme case). Self-hosted ansible-managed runner: no auto-GC, not an issue.\n\n3. **Runner daemon restart between jobs** \u2014 docker daemon restart preserves images on disk (they're in `/var/lib/docker`). OS restart likewise. Only a full storage reset would wipe them.\n\n4. **Using `ACTIONS_RUNNER_DEBUG` or retry shimming** that kills intermediate state \u2014 edge case, non-default.\n\n### Short answer\n\nFor a user with one self-hosted runner installed via the standard ansible playbook, running normal workloads: yes, this works every time. The \"loud failure\" mode only triggers if you've done something unusual to the runner's docker storage between jobs."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
