{"timestamp": "2026-04-24T16:23:52.130809", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/b6280e45-69a0-4be3-81ec-a2d05890506f.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Done \u2014 `CHECKOUT_VER` is now in `project.k.json` under the autopilot spec's envs:\n\n```json\n\"autopilot\": {\n  \"spec_dir\": \"autopilot\",\n  \"envs\": {\n    \"PROJECT_ROOT\": \"autopilot\",\n    \"CHECKOUT_VER\": \"actions/checkout@de0fac2e4500dabe0009e67214ff5f5447ce83dd\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Next step \u2014 using the env var\n\nThe existing constraint `workflow_hygiene/checkout_pinned_to_approved_sha` (in `autopilot/spec.k.json`) currently hardcodes the SHA in its `cmd`. It's verified (`fails_count=1`), so its `cmd` is locked and can't be changed to reference `$CHECKOUT_VER` in place. Two options:\n\n1. **Leave the old constraint** and add a **new** constraint that uses `$CHECKOUT_VER`. The old becomes redundant but can't be removed (locked). You'd end up with two constraints saying roughly the same thing.\n\n2. **Remove and re-add**: delete the verified constraint, add a fresh one whose cmd references `$CHECKOUT_VER`. This needs to work around the \"can't modify verified constraints\" guard \u2014 same dance as before (file-based patch, trigger a verifying failure).\n\n### Question before I proceed\n\nWhich way? Or is just having `CHECKOUT_VER` available in the env enough for now (future constraints can reference it, existing one stays as-is)?"}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
