{"timestamp": "2026-04-24T18:57:47.806751", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "fbd78bc8-61f5-4e68-af04-1a946ee737c7", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/fbd78bc8-61f5-4e68-af04-1a946ee737c7.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "This is correct \u2014 they're complementary, not redundant.\n\n- **`docker/setup-buildx-action`** installs & configures Buildx as a builder instance in the job. One-time setup. Produces no image on its own.\n- **`docker/build-push-action`** is the actual build call. It *requires* a Buildx builder to be present \u2014 without the setup step it falls back to the legacy `docker build` driver, which doesn't support `cache-from/cache-to type=gha`, multi-platform, or `load: true` + cache together.\n\nSo the pattern is always: setup once \u2192 build (possibly multiple times) against that builder.\n\nOne note on the gating: the setup step's `if:` only checks `inputs.dockerfile != '' && steps.local.outputs.hit != 'true'` \u2014 no `is_self_hosted` filter. That's intentional: both the hosted path (line 175) and the self-hosted path (line 188) use `build-push-action`, so both need Buildx configured. The only thing that differs between them is whether the GHA layer cache is wired up."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
