{"timestamp": "2026-04-25T08:46:23.098733", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "9bc3bb23-3a03-4c50-bc77-cab9263aed1b", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/9bc3bb23-3a03-4c50-bc77-cab9263aed1b.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace/autopilot", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "GitHub hard-requires workflow YAMLs to sit directly in `.github/workflows/` \u2014 they're not picked up from subfolders. So we can't literally do \"one folder per workflow.\"\n\nThe closest convention that *does* work: keep each `.github/workflows/<name>.yml` as a thin shim, and put all of its logic + scripts + fixtures in a sibling `.github/actions/<name>/` composite action. The workflow becomes ~10 lines (trigger + `uses: ./.github/actions/<name>`), and everything else \u2014 `action.yml`, `script.sh`, `fixtures/`, helper scripts \u2014 lives in one folder.\n\nFor `act-step-runner` specifically, this would mean:\n- `.github/workflows/act-step-runner.yml` \u2014 thin shim, kept here because GitHub requires it.\n- `.github/actions/act-step-runner/` \u2014 `action.yml`, `dispatch.sh` (moved from `scripts/`), `run-checks.sh` (moved from `scripts/test/`), plus any helpers.\n\nTradeoff: clean colocation and matches the actions convention, but each workflow now has two entry points (the shim and the composite). And `act-step-runner.yml` is a special case \u2014 it has multiple test-wrapper jobs (`parse-issue`, `choose-branch`, `parse-digest`) that aren't easily collapsed into a single composite call, so the shim won't be as thin as for a normal workflow.\n\nWant me to (a) apply this pattern to `act-step-runner` only as a pilot, (b) apply it to all workflows, or (c) just move the two scripts into `.github/actions/act-step-runner/` and leave the workflow as-is?"}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
