{"timestamp": "2026-04-25T08:56:22.277047", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "9bc3bb23-3a03-4c50-bc77-cab9263aed1b", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/9bc3bb23-3a03-4c50-bc77-cab9263aed1b.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace/autopilot", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Could you give me a bit more context \u2014 which knobs do you want to tune, and from where?\n\nPossibilities I can imagine:\n1. **`docker run` flags** for the agent/check-constraints containers (e.g. `--cpus`, `--memory`, extra `-e` vars, `--network`) \u2014 these would surface as new inputs on `coding-agent.yml` / `check-constraints.yml` / `ensure-docker-image.yml`, threaded down into `run-in-docker-claude.sh` / `run-in-docker-no-claude.sh`.\n2. **`docker build` flags** (build args, target, platform) \u2014 surfaced as inputs on `ensure-docker-image.yml` and passed to `docker/build-push-action`.\n3. **Application flags inside the container** (e.g. `claude --debug`, custom env for the agent script) \u2014 passed via workflow inputs \u2192 env \u2192 entrypoint.\n4. **Constraint runner flags** (`--features X`, `--full-report`) \u2014 surfaced as the `command` input on `check-constraints.yml`, which already exists.\n\nWhich of these do you mean, and is the caller a human triggering `workflow_dispatch`, another workflow doing `workflow_call`, or the issue-triggered agent flow? Once I know the specific flag and the caller, I can show the exact wiring."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-25T08:56:33.838721", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "9bc3bb23-3a03-4c50-bc77-cab9263aed1b", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/9bc3bb23-3a03-4c50-bc77-cab9263aed1b.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace/autopilot", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "i mean env variables", "session_title": "autopilot-selftest"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-25T08:57:04.077544", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "9bc3bb23-3a03-4c50-bc77-cab9263aed1b", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/9bc3bb23-3a03-4c50-bc77-cab9263aed1b.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace/autopilot", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "There are three existing patterns in this repo for getting env vars into the container, depending on how stable/structured the var is:\n\n**1. Hard-wired pass-through** (`run-in-docker-claude.sh:26-31`) \u2014 for vars the agent always needs. The script has explicit `-e MODEL`, `-e PROMPT`, etc., and the workflow sets them as job/step `env:`. Use when the var is part of the contract.\n\n**2. `CLAUDE_EXTRA_DOCKER_ARGS` escape hatch** (`run-in-docker-claude.sh:44`) \u2014 appended verbatim to `docker run`. Set it as an `env:` on the workflow step or as a workflow input, then pass `-e FOO=bar -e BAZ=qux` through it. Use when callers want ad-hoc tuning without changing the script. Caveat: claude-side only; `run-in-docker-no-claude.sh` doesn't have an equivalent yet \u2014 easy to add a `NO_CLAUDE_EXTRA_DOCKER_ARGS` if you want it for constraint runs.\n\n**3. Workflow input \u2192 step `env:` \u2192 script** \u2014 the cleanest for one specific knob. Add an `input` to the calling workflow (`workflow_dispatch` or `workflow_call`), wire it into the step's `env:` block, and either reference it directly in `run-in-docker-*.sh` or pass it through `CLAUDE_EXTRA_DOCKER_ARGS`. Example for a new `LOG_LEVEL` knob on `coding-agent.yml`:\n\n```yaml\non:\n  workflow_call:\n    inputs:\n      log_level: { type: string, default: info }\njobs:\n  run-agent:\n    env:\n      CLAUDE_EXTRA_DOCKER_ARGS: -e LOG_LEVEL=${{ inputs.log_level }}\n```\n\nWhich path fits depends on the var: known-and-stable \u2192 option 1; ad-hoc/per-run \u2192 option 2; per-caller policy \u2192 option 3. Tell me which env var you want to plumb and I'll wire the specific path."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
