{"timestamp": "2026-04-26T01:03:16.618371", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "c966cf96-0585-4339-a113-e99e77a184d4", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/c966cf96-0585-4339-a113-e99e77a184d4.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace/autopilot", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Bad naming on my part \u2014 they're unrelated projects, not forks of anything in particular. The relevant thing is \"two GitHub repos that share the same self-hosted runner.\"\n\nRealistic example: you register one self-hosted runner under `@yaroslav`. You enable autopilot on two of your repos:\n- `embucket/data-pipeline`\n- `yaroslav/personal-blog`\n\nBoth call `ensure-docker-image` with `tag_prefix: agent-img`. Result on your runner's daemon:\n\n```\nREPOSITORY        TAG\nautopilot-agent   embucket-data-pipeline-agent-img-<hashA>\nautopilot-agent   yaroslav-personal-blog-agent-img-<hashB>\n```\n\nversus, if `tag_prefix: agent-img` (no repo):\n\n```\nREPOSITORY        TAG\nautopilot-agent   agent-img-<hashA>\nautopilot-agent   agent-img-<hashB>\n```\n\nThe second form is fine *until* the two repos happen to derive the same Dockerfile from the same base \u2014 then both `<hash>` values collide and you get one tag shared between two unrelated projects. The repo prefix prevents that, plus makes `docker images | grep embucket` a useful filter.\n\nSame applies if upstream/fork pairs run autopilot independently (e.g. you maintain a private fork that runs its own agent, and someone else's public fork on the same shared runner does too) \u2014 but the dominant case is just \"your own multiple repos sharing one runner.\""}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-26T01:03:55.568873", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "c966cf96-0585-4339-a113-e99e77a184d4", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/c966cf96-0585-4339-a113-e99e77a184d4.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace/autopilot", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "GitHub does isolate the cache per-repo at the platform level. So why short tag_prefix is not enougH?"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-26T01:04:18.226080", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "c966cf96-0585-4339-a113-e99e77a184d4", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/c966cf96-0585-4339-a113-e99e77a184d4.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace/autopilot", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Short answer: it isn't, on hosted runners \u2014 GHA cache isolation already covers you there. The reason to include `${{ github.repository }}` is **self-hosted only**.\n\nCache (hosted): GHA scopes by repo \u2192 `tag_prefix: agent-img` would never collide with another repo's cache.\n\nDaemon (self-hosted): one docker daemon, all repos that share that runner write tags to it. No GitHub-side isolation. Two repos with `tag_prefix: agent-img` would write to the same tag namespace; if their content hashes ever match, the tag is shared between unrelated projects.\n\nAutopilot specifically targets self-hosted runners (the agent always runs on `[self-hosted, <runner_label>]`), and one runner per user means *all* that user's autopilot-enabled repos share one daemon. So the daemon-collision scenario is the live one \u2014 that's why the example uses `${{ github.repository }}-agent-img`.\n\nIf autopilot were a hosted-only setup, `tag_prefix: agent-img` alone would be sufficient. The repo prefix is paying for the self-hosted reality, not for cache scoping."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
