{"timestamp": "2026-04-26T01:05:12.639369", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "c966cf96-0585-4339-a113-e99e77a184d4", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/c966cf96-0585-4339-a113-e99e77a184d4.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace/autopilot", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Concrete collision scenario.\n\n**Setup:** one self-hosted runner under `@yaroslav`, used by two unrelated repos:\n- `yaroslav/data-pipeline`\n- `yaroslav/personal-blog`\n\nBoth repos use the same minimal `Dockerfile.agent`:\n```dockerfile\nFROM ghcr.io/clockwork-pilot/autopilot-ws:latest\nRUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends ffmpeg\n```\n\nBoth call:\n```yaml\n- uses: clockwork-pilot/autopilot/.github/workflows/ensure-docker-image.yml@v1\n  with:\n    base_image: ghcr.io/clockwork-pilot/autopilot-ws:latest\n    dockerfile: Dockerfile.agent\n    tag:        autopilot-agent\n    tag_prefix: agent-img        # \u2190 short, no repo\n```\n\n**What `ensure-docker-image` computes** (action.yml line 117):\n```\nHASH = sha256(Dockerfile.agent)[:16] - <base-digest> - sha256(build_args)[:16]\n```\n\nBoth repos have byte-identical `Dockerfile.agent`, identical base digest, identical (empty) build args \u2192 **identical hash**, e.g. `a1b2c3d4e5f6g7h8`.\n\n**Composed tag** (line 120, `${TAG_BASE}:${SAFE_PREFIX}-${HASH}`):\n```\nautopilot-agent:agent-img-a1b2c3d4e5f6g7h8\n```\n\nThe same string. Two repos. One docker daemon.\n\n**`data-pipeline` runs first.** Builds the image, tags it `autopilot-agent:agent-img-a1b2c3d4e5f6g7h8`. Agent runs against the data-pipeline workspace.\n\n**`personal-blog` runs ten minutes later.** `ensure-docker-image` does `docker image inspect autopilot-agent:agent-img-a1b2c3d4e5f6g7h8` (action.yml:129) \u2014 finds it. Skips the build. Returns the existing tag.\n\nSo far, fine \u2014 the image content really is identical, reuse is correct.\n\n**Now you edit `data-pipeline/Dockerfile.agent`** to add `libsndfile1`. Hash changes to `b2c3d4...`. New tag `autopilot-agent:agent-img-b2c3d4...`. Agent runs against data-pipeline with the new image. Old `agent-img-a1b2c3...` is still around for personal-blog.\n\n**You also edit `personal-blog/Dockerfile.agent`** independently \u2014 different change, adds `imagemagick`. Hash also lands on, say, `c3d4e5...`. Different tag. Fine.\n\nSo far still fine. The collision risk is real but the dockerfile-content hash usually saves you.\n\n**Where it actually bites:** suppose `data-pipeline` does `docker rmi autopilot-agent:agent-img-a1b2c3...` to clean up an old image (or a cleanup policy / manual prune fires on the runner). That's the *shared* tag. `personal-blog`'s next run will see `docker image inspect` return non-zero, force a rebuild \u2014 wasted minutes, but recoverable.\n\n**Where it bites worse:** any tooling that lists \"agent images for this project\" \u2014 `docker images | grep agent-img-` returns rows from both projects with no way to tell which repo owns which. If you write a cleanup script in `data-pipeline` that prunes \"old agent-img-* tags,\" you'll happily delete `personal-blog`'s active tag.\n\n**With `tag_prefix: ${{ github.repository }}-agent-img`:**\n```\nautopilot-agent:yaroslav-data-pipeline-agent-img-a1b2c3...\nautopilot-agent:yaroslav-personal-blog-agent-img-a1b2c3...\n```\nSame content hash, different tags. No shared row, no shared GC fate, `grep yaroslav-data-pipeline` is a clean filter, cleanup scripts are safe per-project.\n\nThat's the cost of dropping the repo prefix on a shared self-hosted daemon: not \"things break right now,\" but \"things become entangled across unrelated projects.\""}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
