{"timestamp": "2026-04-26T01:06:18.202444", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "c966cf96-0585-4339-a113-e99e77a184d4", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/c966cf96-0585-4339-a113-e99e77a184d4.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace/autopilot", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "You're right \u2014 if every repo's workflow already hardcodes a project-distinct prefix (`data-pipeline-agent-img` vs `blog-agent-img`), there's no collision and `${{ github.repository }}` adds nothing functional.\n\nThe repo interpolation buys three things, all conventional rather than required:\n\n1. **Removes the judgement call.** Author of `data-pipeline/agent.yml` doesn't have to think \"is this prefix globally unique on every machine that might run my workflow?\" \u2014 using `${{ github.repository }}` makes it unique by construction.\n2. **Forks self-distinguish.** If someone forks `data-pipeline` and the workflow file is byte-identical, the fork's `github.repository` differs from upstream's \u2192 fork and upstream don't share cache/tag rows on a runner that happens to run both. With a hardcoded `data-pipeline-agent-img`, the fork would inherit the same prefix and collide on a shared daemon (rare, but the failure mode is silent).\n3. **Self-documenting.** `docker images` and cache logs show the originating repo without the author having to encode it manually.\n\nIf your reality is \"one author, one runner, hand-picked prefix per repo,\" none of those matter \u2014 you can drop `${{ github.repository }}` and the example still works. The convention exists for \"templates that get copy-pasted across many repos by many people,\" which is the autopilot-selftest pitch.\n\nHonest framing: it's defensive defaulting, not a correctness requirement."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
