{"timestamp": "2026-04-26T09:25:31.328308", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "f3f66d06-7f92-4db6-97f8-5f5513c17dd2", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/f3f66d06-7f92-4db6-97f8-5f5513c17dd2.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "didn't get it  Note: steps.agent-commit.outcome will be failure while steps.agent-commit.conclusion is success \u2014 useful if you ever want to branch on it. Want me to drop it (let a  \n  failed commit fail the job) or keep parity with the old behavior?"}}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-26T09:25:47.105848", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "f3f66d06-7f92-4db6-97f8-5f5513c17dd2", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/f3f66d06-7f92-4db6-97f8-5f5513c17dd2.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Every step has two result fields:\n\n- `outcome` \u2014 the raw result before `continue-on-error` is applied. `success` or `failure` based on the exit code.\n- `conclusion` \u2014 the result after `continue-on-error`. With `continue-on-error: true`, a failed step's `conclusion` becomes `success` (so the job keeps going), but `outcome` stays `failure`.\n\nSo if a later step ever wanted to know \"did the commit actually succeed?\", it would check `steps.agent-commit.outcome == 'success'`, not `conclusion`. Right now nothing reads it, so it doesn't matter \u2014 I just mentioned it in case.\n\nThe real question: do you want a failed `Agent commit` to fail the whole job (red), or silently continue like the old `|| true` did? The old code swallowed it, so I kept parity. Say the word and I'll drop `continue-on-error`."}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
