{"timestamp": "2026-04-26T10:23:38.622422", "event": "UserPromptSubmit", "data": {"session_id": "7a1f01a6-1a9b-4c52-a425-29713aa330f7", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/7a1f01a6-1a9b-4c52-a425-29713aa330f7.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "The rule isn't \"reusable vs non-reusable\" \u2014 it's whose checkout sits at $GITHUB_WORKSPACE when the run: executes.                                                     \n                                                                          \n  Where bash .github/scripts/... must NOT exist                                                                                                                         \n                                                                                                                                                                        \n  All workflow files in autopilot/.github/workflows/:                                                                                                                   \n                                                                                                                                                                        \n  - coding-agent.yml                                                                                                                                                    \n  - check-constraints.yml                                         \n  - ensure-docker-image.yml\n  - issue-trigger.yml                                                                                                                                                   \n  - act-step-runner.yml (latent \u2014 see below)\n                                                                                                                                                                        \n  Why: these are all workflow_call reusables. When a consumer invokes them, actions/checkout pulls the consumer's repo into $GITHUB_WORKSPACE. A run: step's working dir\n   is that workspace, so .github/scripts/foo.sh resolves against the consumer's tree \u2014 which doesn't have autopilot's scripts. That's exactly the failure you just hit. \n                                                                                                                                                                        \n  Where it CAN exist                                              \n\n  Composite actions in autopilot/.github/actions/*/action.yml:                                                                                                          \n   \n  - run-agent, check-constraints, ensure-docker-image, parse-issue, choose-branch, comment-agent-result, create-pr                                                      \n                                                                  \n  Why: when a composite action runs, GitHub sets $GITHUB_ACTION_PATH to the directory containing that action.yml \u2014 i.e. the autopilot repo checkout fetched implicitly  \n  by the uses: resolver. So bash \"$GITHUB_ACTION_PATH/../../scripts/foo.sh\" finds autopilot's own scripts regardless of what's in $GITHUB_WORKSPACE. The two paths are\n  independent.                                                                                                                                                          \n                                                                  \n  The exception\n\n  act-step-runner.yml line 32 still does bash .github/scripts/test/act-step-dispatch.sh. It works today only because autopilot's own CI is the only caller and          \n  actions/checkout happens to fetch autopilot. If anyone else workflow_calls it, it breaks the same way. Same fix applies \u2014 wrap the dispatch logic in a composite\n  action, or document that this workflow is autopilot-internal only.                                                                                                    \n                                                                  \n  The guard\n\n  Single grep enforces the rule for the workflows directory:                                                                                                            \n   \n  ! grep -nE '^\\s*run:.*\\.github/scripts/' .github/workflows/*.yml                                                                                                      \n                                                                                                                                                                        \n  Composite actions are exempt (they use $GITHUB_ACTION_PATH, which the regex doesn't match).  If task is clear create constraint"}}
