{"timestamp": "2026-04-26T12:08:47.812887", "event": "Stop", "status": "allowed", "data": {"session_id": "7a1f01a6-1a9b-4c52-a425-29713aa330f7", "transcript_path": "/home/node/.claude/projects/-workspace/7a1f01a6-1a9b-4c52-a425-29713aa330f7.jsonl", "cwd": "/workspace", "permission_mode": "bypassPermissions", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "The issue is in `run-in-docker-claude.sh`: when GitHub cancels, the runner SIGTERMs the bash step, but `docker run --rm` doesn't reliably kill the container \u2014 the daemon keeps it alive even after the client exits, so the agent keeps churning.\n\nFix: capture the container ID via `--cidfile` and install a trap that runs `docker kill` on EXIT/INT/TERM. Also wrap with `timeout --foreground` so signals propagate through `timeout` to `docker run` in the first place.\n\nSketch:\n```bash\nCIDFILE=$(mktemp -u)\ntrap 'CID=$(cat \"$CIDFILE\" 2>/dev/null || true); [ -n \"$CID\" ] && docker kill \"$CID\" 2>/dev/null; rm -f \"$CIDFILE\"' EXIT INT TERM\nRUN=(timeout --foreground \"$TIMEOUT_SECS\" docker run --rm --cidfile \"$CIDFILE\" ...)\n```\n\nSame fix likely needed in `run-in-docker-no-agent.sh` (constraint check container has the same problem).\n\nWant me to apply it to both scripts and add a constraint that asserts the cidfile/trap pattern is present?"}, "vars": {"PROJECT_ROOT": "/workspace", "PLUGIN_ROOT": "/plugin", "WORKSPACE_ROOT": "/workspace"}}
